<BODY BGCOLOR=#E0A0AO>
<BODY>

<H1><B><A NAME="top"></A></B></H1>
<P align=center><IMG SRC="gifs/logosm.gif" ALT="dotPHARMACY logo"></P>
<P>
<H1 align=center><B>1996-97 offer to NHS contractors</B></H1>


<P align=center><I>The full text of the current Department of Health offer (published on dotPHARMACY February 3)  and PSNC reaction are retained on this page for reference</I></P>
<P>
Pharmacists have been offered a &quot;derisory&quot; 2.5% on the
global sum for dispensing NHS prescriptions in 1996-97 - but other
remuneration elements would be frozen or reduced.
<P>
The Pharmaceutical Services Negotiating Committee is rejecting
the Department of Health's offer, summarising its main proposals
as :-
<P>
<UL>
<LI>A freeze in the level of the dispensing fee
<LI>A reduction in the value of the professional allowance, both on the graduated prescription scale and above the 1,600 prescriptions threshold
<LI>No change in the level of any other fees
<LI>An increase in the amount of the global sum money devolved to local level in an effort to take account of the large number of homes already receiving advice from contractors
<LI>A refusal to consider having national fees for the services which are devolved for local management</LI>
</UL>
<P>
The full text of the DoH offer is :-
<P>
1995/96 saw the fruition of our plans to restructure fees within
the global sum. We have shifted the emphasis away from piece rate
services, and have made explicit recognition of the professional
role that pharmacists play by introducing a professional allowance.
<P>
You have suggested that productivity and efficiency are measured
largely by the volume of NHS prescriptions dispensed. I agree
that when the global sum was paid out almost entirely by way of
dispensing fee, the number of prescriptions dispensed was one
of the few measures that we had available for assessing productivity.
With the shift in emphasis mentioned above, we would expect to
consider a widening of the professional role of pharmacists as
well as increases in dispensing volume. As in recent years any
increase in pay can only be justified if there is a rise in productivity.
<P>
You have expressed the view that the current level of core gross
profit is having a de-motivating effect on contractor pharmacists.
The Department's aim is that, as a healthcare profession, community
pharmacy is properly paid for the professional services it provides;
that it is reimbursed the net acquisition cost of the medicines
dispensed, assuming a cost effective purchasing strategy; and
that the level of the global sum is set at a level that means
that expenses such as the difference in the time at which medicines
are bought and are reimbursed can be met.
<P>
I am aware, of course, that it was agreed during the 1995/96 pay
negotiations that we should look at your concerns about working
capital. We have thoroughly examined the problems you have presented
to us. Our calculations suggest that since the introduction of
the global sum the fall of interest rates has more than compensated
for the increase in the drugs bill. We believe that on the basis
of the assumptions that we normally use to calculate the time
between a pharmacist paying for stock on average, and being paid
for prescriptions dispensed the amount required for working capital
as a consequence of the payment schedule has fallen in cash terms
(let alone real terms) since 1989. We have discussed this with
 officers of the Committee, and look forward to your comments
on our analysis of the situation.
<P>
In the light of the above, Ministers have agreed that we should
make the following offer for 1996/97. The calculations are based
on the assumption of a 1 April implementation date. Should that
prove not to be achievable the actual level of the fees will be
determined by the date of the settlement:
<P>
(i) an increase to the global sum of 2.5% taking it to &#163;688.5m.
This would be the sum which would determine the application of
the trigger mechanism. This is conditional on your agreement to
the devolution of the Domicillary Oxygen Cylinder Service to local
management in 1996/97. Also, it is made on the basis that you
will accept the offer made to you previously that a fee of 40p
should be payable for each prescription for a Schedule 3 Controlled
Drug, including temazepam, from 1 April 1996 onwards.
<P>
(ii) a flat rate dispensing fee of 94.6pence. This is the same
rate as for 1995/96, and any increases in income from dispensing
will, therefore come from increases in activity. We are assuming
a national average increase in prescription volume of 3%;
<P>
(iii)  a professional allowance of &#163;735 which would be payable
each month to pharmacies which have priced 1,100 or more
prescriptions in the relevant month rising to &#163;1,290 at 1,600
prescriptions. In addition, contractors with whom an arrangement
has been made would need to continue to meet the other qualifying
conditions we have previously agreed. This is a reduction in the
level of the professional allowance which is proposed in recognition
of the fact that the threshold number of prescriptions for qualification
for payment are being held at the level of 1995/96, and that in
view of the comments in your letter, we have not sought any new
criteria for eligibility.
<P>
(iv) all other fees should remain at the 1995/96 level with any
increases in pay being consequent in activity.
<P>
You have asked me to consider having national fees for the services
which are devolved for local management. We cannot agree to this.
We wish Health Authorities to have as much freedom as possible
to manage the services locally in the best interests of their
population.
<P>
There has been a very considerable rise in the number of homes
which are receiving advice in the safe keeping and administration
of medicines. In recognition of this we would like to propose
that within the overall total of the global sum, the amount which
was devolved in 1995/96 for management of specified services at
local level should be increased by 5%, Health Authorities being
advised that we would expect the bulk of the increase to be used
for services to homes. We believe that this is broadly in line
with your request.
<HR>
