<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>dotPHARMACY: Chemex forum</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR=#80FF80>
<CENTER>
<h1>Chemex Forum</h1>
<h3>Debating the system for reporting ADRs</h3></CENTER>
<p><br><CENTER>

<STRONG>Should there be an adverse drug reaction reporting system for OTC medicines through community pharmacies? This question was put to an expert panel at a Chemex forum organised jointly by C&D and Roche Consumer Health</STRONG></CENTER>
<p>
<center>
<TABLE BORDER="2" WIDTH="300">

<TR VALIGN="top">

<td>
<CENTER>

<H4>Members of the panel</H4>
<STRONG>Sheila Kelly</STRONG> director, Proprietary Association of Great Britain; <STRONG>Roger Odd</STRONG> head of the Royal Pharmaceutical Society's practice division; <STRONG>Claire Anderson</STRONG> lecturer in community pharmacy, King's College, London; and <STRONG>Larry Goodyear</STRONG> lecturer in clinical pharmacy, King's College.

</center>
</tr>
</table></center>
<P >
The Medicines Control Agency has agreed in principle to extend the official adverse drug reaction (ADR) reporting system to pharmacists and the Royal Pharmaceutical Society is looking into the feasibility of a national scheme for hospital pharmacists. 
<P>
Chairman Patrick Grice said that, as far as he was aware, there was no system for community pharmacists to report reactions to over the counter medicines and it would be a world first for the UK if pharmacists became involved. 
<P>
Sheila Kelly maintained that the UK already had a system for reporting reactions to OTC medicines, but it did not differentiate between these and prescription medicines. If customers experienced a severe reaction to an OTC product, they could complain to the company or could go to a GP for medical advice. In either case, the company or doctor was obliged to report the incident to the MCA. 
<P>
She thought that there would be fewer reactions to OTC products as safety was a major factor in deciding whether medicines should be available without prescription.
<P>
Roger Odd argued that, although a system was in place, the reports still had to go through a doctor. ''In many cases, the doctor might not even be aware that the patient had taken a non-prescription medicine,'' he said. ''Why shouldn't a pharmacist - with all his experience of knowing how drugs work, plus the fact that people buy non-prescription medicines from pharmacies - be in as good a position as any other professional in the healthcare team to report reactions directly to the MCA and ultimately to the companies themselves?''
<P>
Such a system was long overdue, he said. Any system would have to be acceptable to the MCA and the industry, and pharmacists would need to be trained what to report and how to report it. But to stop pharmacists being involved would not be in the public interest, particularly as more potent medicines were becoming widely available.
<P>
The Society had put forward a case to the MCA for community pharmacists to be involved in reporting adverse reactions to both prescription and non-prescription medicines, he explained. The MCA was soon expected to circulate a consultative paper to all interested parties - pharmacists, the industry and the medical profession - suggesting possible schemes. 
<P>
One option might be for pharmacists to fill in the existing yellow cards. The Society was insisting on links with prescribers, so pharmacists would know about the patient's condition and what other medicines were being taken.
<P>
Initial discussions with the British Medical Association suggested that doctors would be happy with pharmacists reporting ADRs, providing they were involved in the consultation process and received copies of reports sent to the MCA. The Society would like to see schemes in place as soon as possible after the consultations, but it could take some time to agree the guidelines within which pharmacists should operate, and to train them to report the right information. Hospital pharmacists were already being trained for this function.
<P>
Larry Goodyear, who has been looking at the feasibility of running clinical trials through community pharmacies, said that most safety data on OTC medicines came from trials in which the medicines were prescribed by GPs - a totally different population from that buying treatments from pharmacies. Sometimes OTC products were used for different indications and at different doses. 
<P>
He agreed that pharmacists were ideally placed to collect that type of data. But he wondered whether the average community pharmacist had the breadth of clinical knowledge or enough supporting information about patients. In hospitals, pharmacists would have access to the patient's notes.
<P>
Claire Anderson believed many pharmacists had enough clinical knowledge, while others would need bringing up to the right level. Some were not sufficiently involved in selling OTC medicines in their pharmacies. Hopefully, pharmacy training in schools would prepare graduates for this task.
<P>
Ms Kelly pointed out that for many POM to P switches, the indications were the same as when the product was on prescription. For others, such as ibuprofen, the prescription version had been taken day in day out for several years, possibly at high doses. In general, people now buying these medicines were younger, healthier and perhaps using the products intermittently, so the safety profile was likely to be better. 
<P>
The MCA was reluctant to switch medicines until it was confident there would be no problems with unsupervised use in the general population. Most people believed that the ADR profile of a molecule was established within three years of marketing and that a medicine could not become available off prescription until it had been on the market for at least five years.
<P>
She went on to say that most OTC purchases were repeats - about 86 per cent of people bought a medicine they had used before, so one could assume that if it caused problems, they would not still be using it. She saw pharmacists playing a valuable role in advising on medicines which patients were using for the first time and asking on a later occasion if the medicine had been suitable. ''That would give valuable feedback between the customer and the pharmacist,'' she said. She agreed that pharmacists should be involved in ADR collection and thought that there was no case for separate schemes for OTC and prescription medicines.
<P>
When asked how easy it would be in practice to identify ADRs, Mr Goodyear said it would depend on the pharmacist's clinical knowledge and the severity of the reaction. If people were not particularly worried about a reaction, they would keep it to themselves. Pharmacists tended to have a core of clients who used the pharmacy regularly and whose medical background was well known.
<P>
''In some cases, the pharmacist might be better placed to report ADRs than the GP, who might not have the same insight, as he does not see the patient as regularly,'' he said.
<P>
His experience of hospital practice was that pharmacists could refer to the patient's notes and encourage ADR reporting by filling in forms which were then signed by the registrar. He envisaged a similar system in the community, where the pharmacist identified the problem but collaborated with the GP in reporting. If the pharmacist just said to the GP, ''I think that there's an ADR'', the problem might not get reported.
<P>
Mr Odd agreed it was easier for hospital pharmacists to establish links with prescribers and obtain patient profiles. The Society was discussing with the MCA ways in which such a system could be achieved in the community. Ms Anderson thought there might be some initial problems persuading doctors to release information, because of patient confidentiality. 
<P>
When asked if PAGB member companies would be comfortable with an ADR reporting system involving OTC medicines, Ms Kelly said she did not think there would be any objections. Companies would want to know if their products were not suiting people, she said: ''It would all add to the safety net that we're trying to achieve.''
<P>


<hr>
<p>
