<HEAD>

<TITLE>dotPHARMACY: education</TITLE>

<META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Internet Assistant for Word 1.0Z">
<META NAME="AUTHOR" CONTENT="Ron Salmon">
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR=#E0A0A0>
<BODY>

<H1><B><A NAME="top"></A></B></H1>
<P align=center><IMG SRC="gifs/logosm.gif" ALT="Chemist & Druggist logo"></P>
<P>
<H1><B>Continuing education in community pharmacy</B></H1>

<H1><B> -- the facts and the myths</B></H1>

<P>
All professionals need continuing education to help them maintain and develop the service they provide to clients throughout their
working life. Pharmacists and their staff are no different and need to keep abreast of both technical innovations and product
developments, and to match the changing needs and aspirations of both the public and the Health Service. But what they must
do, should do and could do all need to be clearly understood. Here, we endeavour to explain what it really means to pharmacists
and their teams.
<HR>
<A NAME="a">
<H3><B></A>Assistant training - the mystery explained</B>
</H3>

<P>
By July 1 1996, assistants working on  the pharmacy medicines counter needed to have completed, or be taking, a course that
satisfies the Royal Pharmaceutical Society's knowledge base requirements, centred on NVQ217. 
<P>
Assistants who have taken the following courses, or who had completed them by December 31, 1996, have fulfilled the Society's demands:
<P>
1.  Distributive Occupational Standards Council (DOSC)-approved  retail NVQ level 2 courses, such as those provided by the Royal
Society of the Arts and City and Guilds. New staff will be able to take these courses in the future.
<P>
2. NPA Medicine Counter Assistant Course (units 1, 2 and top-up), and the equivalent course run by Boots the Chemists for their staff.
<P>
3. RPSGB-set Multiple Choice Question papers taken by &quot;experienced assistants&quot; in January or December 1996. Assistants have two chances to take the MCQ, which is  taken in the pharmacy under the supervision of a pharmacist in defined, controlled conditions. The Society defines an &quot;experienced assistant&quot; as a person who has worked on the medicines counter for at least 16
hours a week for at least three of the last five years.
<P>
4. Courses accredited by the College of Pharmacy Practice. <I>C&ampD's</I> Cambridge Counterpart Pharmacy Assistant Development Programme is an accredited course.
<HR>
<A NAME="b"></A>
<H3><B>Continuing education for pharmacists - the accreditation jungle</B></H3>

<P>
Continuing education for pharmacists is not mandatory.  However, although the Royal Pharmaceutical Society (RPSGB), in its Code
of Ethics, suggests that pharmacists should undertake a minimum of 30 hours of continuing education a year, in July 1995 it shied
away from making a straight &quot;yes&quot; or &quot;no&quot; decision on whether  CE should be mandatory. 
<P>
RPSGB Council agreed &quot;in principle&quot; to 'put in place a process for verifying pharmacists' compliance with the Code's
expectation' on the matter, and to look at how much it would all cost!  That process is now underway, but no timescale has yet
been set by the Society.
<P>
<H5><B>Points to note</B></H5>

<P>
a) As yet, the RPSGB Council has not defined what constitutes one hour's worth of CE. 
<P>
b) The only other pharmacy body requiring members to undertake CE is the College of Pharmacy Practice.  CPP members must complete
20 hours' worth of CE a year on CPP-accredited courses, logging compliance with the College by submitting course completion certificates.
<P>
c) While the Royal Pharmaceutical Society is likely to recognise one hour's learning on a CPP-accredited course as registering
one hour off its 30 hours annual CE expectation, it has not formally said as much, nor has it recognised courses provided by any other body for this purpose.
<P>
d) Any body can accredit continuing education, but until that body is recognised by the RPSGB as a provider of accredited courses
for its purposes, then hours spent learning will be of  no value in meeting the Society's  CE requirements whenever, and if, they
are formalised. 
<P>
e)  To date  only certain courses provided by the UK's  four CPPEs have been accredited by the College of Pharmacy Practice for use by pharmacists, along with some technical articles in the pharmaceutical Press.  <I>Chemist &amp; Druggist's</I> <a href="upmain.html">Pharmacy Update</a> includes accredited and assessed articles with monthly questionnaires and an optional telephone marking system.

<P>
f) Health Commissions may require community pharmacists contracted to supply pharmaceutical services, to fulfil various requirements, which could include completion of courses and on-going professional development through CE.<P>
In short, only pharmacists who are members of the CPP have any mandatory requirement to participate in CE, although all members
of the RPSGB and Pharmaceutical Society of Northern Ireland will wish to develop professionally. Until the Society defines what
is required explicitly, and makes CE mandatory for continuance in practice, the choice of course is left to the individual.
<P>
<A HREF="#top">Top of page</A>
<P>
<A HREF="#a">Back to assistant training</A>
<P>
<A HREF="#b">Back to pharmacist continuing education</A>
