<HTML>

<HEAD>

<TITLE>dotPHARMACY: Certificate</TITLE>


</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="gifs/back.gif">

<P>
<A NAME="top"></A>
<P align=center><IMG SRC="gifs/cert2.gif" ALT="Certificate logo"></P>
<P>
<H1 align=center><B>All you and your business need</B></H1>
<P align=center><IMG SRC="gifs/redhed2.gif" ALT="Certificate logo"></P>
<P>




Today, more than at any other time, community pharmacists need to be able to practise effectively both as healthcare professionals and as business people. The NHS supplier/provider free market does not give automatic respect to people or professions. Individual pharmacists and their businesses have to be able to practise what they preach - to deliver services required by patients or their health authorities accurately, cost-effectively and when and where required.
<P>
The first stage in the Certificate in Community Pharmacy Management comprises ten free monthly learning modules that will help you get to grips with the business practise skills needed to manage your community pharmacy in this ever more competitive environment. 
<p>
The modules are free, only to Chemist &amp; Druggist subscribers or to pharmacists/pharmacies which are on the requested mailing list for Community Pharmacy. Both magazines belong to Miller Freeman Pharmacy Group.
<p>
<CENTER><H3>Distance learning for the community pharmacist business professional</H3></CENTER>

The ten-part modular course will be delivered free in Chemist &amp; Druggist and Community Pharmacy every month through to September 1997 thanks to support from SmithKline Beecham Consumer Healthcare.
<p>
Each module will cover a specifice business skill and will include a number of relevant case studies and 40 self-test true/false questions.
<p>
The ten modules comprise the first 50 hours of the 100-hour certificate in Community Pharmacy developed by the School of Pharmacy, The Queen's University, Belfast.
<p>
The second 50 hour section consists of five ten-hour projects set by the university every six weeks from January 1997. They will be marked sequentially and moderated by the university - pharmacists must complete and pass each project before the next is issued. Pharmacists registered for both parts will have access to a course tutor.
<p>
Students who pass will be awarded a Certificate in Community Pharmacy Management by the School of Pharmacy, The Queen's University, Belfast. The first awards are expected in Autumn of 1997.
<p>
Qualifying pharmacists can obtain further information by emailing <A HREF="mailto:chemdrug@dotpharmacy.com">chemdrug@dotpharmacy.com</a> for the attention of Sue Cheesman or Claire Newman
<HR>

<A HREF="#top">Top of page</A>
<P>

<P align=center><A HREF="http://www.dotpharmacy.co.uk/content1.html"><IMG SRC="gifs/contgrn1.gif" ALT="dotPHARMACY contents page"></A>
<P>
