<HTML><BODY><p>
<CENTER>TRI-SERVICE CADD/GIS/FM SYMPOSIUM '97<BR>
</CENTER><CENTER>&amp;<BR>
</CENTER><CENTER>US ARMY CORPS OF ENGINEERS AND NOAA<br>
</CENTER><CENTER>SURVEYING, MAPPING AND REMOTE SENSING CONFERENCE <br>
</CENTER><p>
<CENTER>18 - 22 AUGUST 1997<p>
</CENTER><p>
<p>
<u>SPONSORED BY</u>:<p>
<p>
TRI-SERVICE CADD/GIS TECHNOLOGY CENTER 	<p>
<p>
HEADQUARTERS, U.S. ARMY CORPS OF ENGINEERS<p>
<p>
NATIONAL OCEANIC AND ATMOSPHERIC ADMINISTRATION,<p>
	NATIONAL OCEAN SERVICE<p>
<p>
U.S. NAVY FACILITIES ENGINEERING COMMAND 	<p>
<p>
U.S. AIR FORCE CIVIL ENGINEER<p>
<p>
U.S. ARMY ASSISTANT CHIEF OF STAFF FOR INSTALLATION MANAGEMENT<p>
<p>
U.S. ARMY COLD REGIONS RESEARCH AND ENGINEERING LABORATORY,<br>
	RS/GIS CENTER	<p>
	 	<p>
U.S. ARMY TOPOGRAPHIC ENGINEERING CENTER,<br>
	TOPOGRAPHIC DEVELOPMENTS LABORATORY<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<u>HOSTED BY</u>:<p>
U.S. Army Engineer District, St. Louis<p>
<p>
<p>
<u>LOCATION</u>:<br>
ADAM'S MARK HOTEL<br>
Fourth and Chestnut Streets<br>
St. Louis, MO 63102<br>
<p>
<p>
<u>GENERAL</u>:<br>
The Tri-Services CADD/GIS Technology Center, U.S. Army Corps of Engineers (USACE), and NOAA will conduct concurrent symposiums in St. Louis, MO during the week of 18 August 1997.  Technical sessions, workshops, and exhibits will address: CADD/GIS facility engineering and management applications, CADD in military construction, civil works CADD/GIS, surveying, mapping, hydrography, and remote sensing. A major training objective of both meetings is to demonstrate new technologies and their implementation in Federal work. These concurrent meetings are also designed to promote information exchange among government agencies, commercial contractors, equipment manufactures, software vendors, and private survey and mapping organizations. <p>
<p>
Representatives from Army installations, Corps of Engineers, Navy, Air Force, and NOAA, as well as other Federal agencies, will attend.  In addition, A-E service contractors, equipment manufacturers, and software application developers are invited to participate. Program topics, technical sessions, workshops, and exhibits will include:<p>
<p>
<u>Tri-Service CADD/GIS/FM Symposium '97</u><p>
<p>
<H4>Networking/Communications</H4><br>
	Using Internet/Intranet Resources<br>
	System Administration<br>
	VRML (Virtual Reality on the Network)<br>
	Video Conferencing<br>
<H4>Facilities Management and Planning</H4><br>
	Implementing CADD-based Facility Management Systems<br>
<H4>Business Practices</H4><br>
	Electronic Document Management Systems and Field Implementations<br>
	Productivity Successes<br>
	Project/Drawing Archiving<br>
<H4>Emerging Technologies</H4><br>
	Object Technologies for Design<br>
	Rule/knowledge-based Systems<br>
	Multimedia Integration<br>
<H4>CADD-based Design Applications</H4><br>
	Automated Specifications<br>
	Automated Cost Estimating<br>
	Interior Design<br>
	Animation and Visualization <br>
	Successful Uses of 3rd Party Design Applications<br>
	Parametric Design<br>
<H4>Construction</H4><br>
	Project/Schedule Management<br>
	As-Built Documentation<br>
<H4>Data Standards</H4><br>
	Industry Alliance for Interoperability Activities<br>
	Workspaces for A/E/C Design<br>
	Electronic Bid Sets<br>
	CADD and Geospatial Data Standardization Activities<br>
	National Spatial Data Infrastructure/FGDC<br>
	Corporate Information Management Initiatives<br>
<H4>GIS Implementations</H4><br>
	Space Management<br>
	Master Planning<br>
	Utilities/Infrastructure Management<br>
	Natural and Cultural Resources Management<br>
	Environmental Data Modeling, Cleanup, and Site Characterization<br>
	Landscape Management<br>
	Coastal and Inland Navigation &amp; Flood Control Projects<br>
	Historic Site Preservation<br>
	Cadastral Analysis<br>
<p>
<u>US Army Corps of Engineers/NOAA Surveying, Mapping and Remote Sensing Conference.</u><p>
<u></u><p>
<H4>Civil Works GIS</H4><br>
	Imagery and GIS<br>
	Emergency Management<br>
	Water Control<br>
	GIS and Model Integration<br>
	Real Time GIS<br>
	3- and 4-D GIS<br>
	Real Estate Applications<br>
	Environmental Applications<br>
	Natural and Water Resources Management<br>
	Project Management<br>
	Permitting and Regulatory Applications<br>
	FGDC GIS Standards<br>
	Master Planning<br>
	GIS and GPS Integration<br>
<p>
<H4>Surveying and Mapping</H4><br>
	Multibeam Hydrographic Surveying<br>
	Hydrographic Survey Technology<br>
	ECDIS/Nautical Charting<br>
	Topographic Survey Technology <br>
	Structural Deformation Monitoring<br>
	Differential GPS Surveying<br>
	Field Data Collection for GIS<br>
	Advanced Photogrammetric Techniques<br>
	Terrain Visualization<br>
	Tides and Water Levels<br>
	Professional Services Contracting<br>
	Data Processing and Adjustments<br>
	Airborne GPS<br>
	Digital Orthophoto Images<br>
<p>
<H4>Remote Sensing</H4><br>
	Remote Sensing/Image Processing<br>
	Flood Inundation Mapping<br>
	Hyperspectral Data Utilization<br>
	Airborne Hydrographic Survey Systems<br>
	Water Control Data Systems<br>
	Data Translation Techniques<br>
	Classification Methods<br>
	Utilization of Remote Sensing Data in ACOE Models<br>
	New/Innovative Sensor Technologies<br>
	Post Processing Methodologies<br>
	High Resolution Satellite Systems<br>
<p>
<p>
The 1997 Symposium is open to any individual or group interested in the various surveying, mapping, remote sensing and CADD/GIS disciplines.<p>
<p>
<p>
<u>SYMPOSIUM FACILITIES</u>:<p>
All technical sessions and exhibits will be held at the St. Louis Adam's Mark Hotel at Fourth and Chestnut Streets, about 2 blocks from the Mississippi River.  An outdoor area will be provided on the river bank to demonstrate topographic, hydrographic, and GPS survey equipment.  Docking facilities will also be available at this site to board hydrographic survey vessels.<p>
<p>
<p>
<u>SYMPOSIUM FEES AND REGISTRATION</u>:<p>
Registration for the symposiums may be performed in advance by mail or on site beginning Monday 18 August, 1997. Due to limited space at some of the workshops, advanced registrations is strongly recommended.  To receive a registration package, preliminary agenda, and to enroll in specific workshops, you must contact the St. Louis District at the following address:<br>
(e-mail contact is encouraged) <p>
<p>
U.S. ARMY ENGINEER DISTRICT, ST. LOUIS<br>
ATTN: CELMS-ED-HG (BOB MESKO)<br>
1222 SPRUCE STREET<br>
ST. LOUIS, MO 63103-2833<br>
		or<br>
E-MAIL: conference@smtp.lms.usace.army.mil<br>
<p>
Interested parties should periodically visit the St. Louis District home page: http://www.lms.usace.army.mil for updates and current information. You should receive a registration package by mail or e-mail before April 1997.  A nominal registration fee may be charged for these symposiums and workshopS--details will be included in the registration package.<p>
<p>
<p>
<u>HOTEL RESERVATIONS</u>:<p>
Special commercial rates of $119.00 single, or $129.00 double and Government per diem rates have been obtained from the Adams Mark Hotel.  A block of rooms at these special rates will be held until 25 July 1997.  Room  reservations should be made directly with the hotel  by mail or phone.  In order to obtain the special rates, be  sure to  mention this  symposium when  making  reservations.  To obtain the  tax inclusive Government per diem rate, Federal  employees  must  present  valid travel orders and  identification upon registration at  the hotel.  Airport shuttle service is available for $10.00 each way or $15.00, round trip.  The hotel self parking garage rate is $12.00 per day. Valet parking is available at $14.00 per day.<p>
<p>
Adam's Mark Hotel<br>
Attn:  Reservations	<br>
Fourth and Chestnut Street	<br>
St. Louis, MO 63102<br>
(314) 241-7400<br>
(314) 241-6618 (FAX)<br>
	<p>
<p>
<u>CALL FOR TECHNICAL PAPERS</u>:<br>
Technical papers will be presented by both government and private representatives on (1) surveying and mapping, (2) remote sensing, (3) GIS, (4) CADD and, (5) facility management topics.  Authors are encouraged to submit 100 - 300 word abstracts for presentation consideration by 15 January 1997. Selected papers must be submitted in camera-ready form by 15 May 1997. Instructions for submitting abstracts may be obtained from:<p>
<p>
Mr. Toby Wilson<br>
USACE Waterways Experiment Station	<br>
ATTN: CEWES-ID-C<br>
3909 Halls Ferry Road<br>
Vicksburg, MS 39180-6199<br>
Telephone: (601) 634-3604<br>
FAX:(601) 634-4584<br>
Email: wilsonj@ex1.wes.army.mil<br>
home page: http:\\mr2.wes.army.mil<br>
<p>
<p>
<u>CALL FOR EXHIBITORS</u>:<br>
Government agencies, commercial firms, service firms, and software/hardware vendors are invited to participate in the exhibit hall and demonstrate their products.  Individual booth spaces will be available at the Adams Mark Hotel.  An outdoor area for demonstrating topographic, GPS, or other technologies will also be provided. In addition, sufficient dock space along the Mississippi River will be reserved to support any exhibitors desiring to demonstrate hydrographic or marine geophysical survey equipment. Exhibit space will be provided for a fee to any interested organization.  Space will be allocated on a first come, first serve basis.<p>
<p>
Exhibits are being coordinated by the Management Association for Private Photogrammetric Surveyors (MAPPS).  For further<br>
information, contact:<br>
<p>
John Palatiello, MAPPS Executive Director<br>
12020 Sunrise Valley Drive, Suite 100<br>
Reston, VA 20191<br>
Telephone: (703) 391-2739  FAX: (703) 476-2217,<br>
e-mail: JOHNMAPPS@AOL.COM<br>
<p>
	<p>
<u>EXHIBIT HOURS</u>:<br>
Tuesday		19 August	0930-1700<br>
Tuesday		19 August	1800-2000 <br>
Wednesday		20 August	0930-1700<br>
Wednesday		20 August	1800-2000<br>
Thursday	     21 August	0930-1630<br>
<p>
<p>
<u>ADDITIONAL INFORMATION</u>:<br>
The U.S. Army, Engineer District, St. Louis is performing overall on site coordination of the symposium training sessions and related activities.  Additional information regarding events not covered or referenced in this brochure may be obtained by contacting:<br>
<p>
Mr. Brad Strauser or Mr. Bob Mesko<br>
U.S. Army Engineer, District, St. Louis<br>
(314) 331-8385 or FAX: (314) 331-8677 <br>
