 </SELECT>


AND/OR for a spatial search, choose a bounding box <p>
in latitude and longitude (decimal degrees). <br>
Please remember that longitudes in the U.S. are negative. <br>

 <pre>
            N  <input SIZE=10 Name=nbndgcoord value=""> <br>
W  <input SIZE=10 Name=wbndgcoord value="">             <input SIZE=10 Name=ebndgcoord value=""> E <br>
            S  <input SIZE=10 Name=sbndgcoord value=""> <br>
 </pre>
 <hr>
Maximum Results:  <SELECT SIZE=1 NAME="maxhits">
 <OPTION> 10
 <OPTION> 20
 <OPTION SELECTED> 40
 <OPTION> 100
 <OPTION> 200
 <OPTION> 1000
 </SELECT>

Form Actions:

 <input TYPE="submit" value="Search">    
 <input TYPE="reset" value="Clear Form"> <br>

 </form>
 <hr>
 <A NAME="help"> <H3>Details on the search query form... </H3> </A>

This form collects search terms which are formulated into WAIS queries by several
intermediate perl scripts.
 <A NAME="Keywords">
 <H3>Search Keywords </H3>
Type into this box any words which are relevant to the topic you are
looking for.  Enter as many as you want, up to 40 characters total (the
entry box will scroll as necessary).  At the present time, this field 
is global for the document, so it finds matching words no matter
what field of the metadata it appeared in. In the future, 
searches on Theme_Keyword and Place_Keyword will be implemented.
 <!-- To aid your searches we have provided an
  <A HREF = "http://badger.state.wi.us/agencies/wlib/sco/pages/globalphindx.html">alphabetical </A>
 and a  <A HREF = "http://badger.state.wi.us/agencies/wlib/sco/pages/globfreqindx.html">frequency </A> 
listing of words contained in these metadata documents. -->
 <P> 
These are the essential characteristics of the Search Keyword Field: <BR>
 <UL>
 <LI>Boolean operations are supported
 <blockquote>
By default, all keywords are logically ORed.  To find documents that contain
all of several keywords, use AND.  To exclude documents based on keywords, use 
NOT. Use parenthesis to construct complex queries.
 </blockquote> 
 <LI>Word proximity has no effect
 <blockquote>
The index is created wordwise, thus it will find documents that contain as a seqential string
the keywords you have supplied, and documents that contain the individual keywords, but separated 
in the document.  For example
using  <EM>tax parcel </EM> in the Search Keywords field will find documents that contain the strings
 <EM>tax parcel </EM>, or  <EM>take this parcel down to the tax assessor's office </EM>. 
 </blockquote>
 <LI>Case insensitive
 <LI>Will not find synonyms (yet)
 <blockquote>
A search for hydrology will not find documents that do not contain the word hydrology, but do
contain the words river or lake.  In the future we hope to be able to implement synonym
searching.
 </blockquote>
 </UL>
 <H3>AND/OR for a spatial search... </H3>
This is a little misleading, sorry.  What it means is that you can do a keyword search
 <EM>only </EM>, and not further limit the search results by also specifying a spatial region 
(note that no county or geographic region is initially selected).  OR you can do a spatial search  <EM>only </EM> by specifying the search area, but not specifying any keywords. You
make your search more specific by supplying keywords AND a spatial region. 

 <H3>a bounding box in latitude and longitude (decimal degrees) </H3>
Hats off to anyone who knows the bounding box for Outagamie county in latitude and longitude.  If your mind works this way, however, maybe you've forgotten that latitude goes in the north and south boxes.  Don't get fancy with degrees minutes seconds.  This system only supports decimal degrees, like, e.g. -89.4435
 <H3>Search </H3>
At a minimim, you will get one result returned from the search.  If you are unlucky, your search produced no results, and the returned document will just be an index of all the documents contained in this index.  If you were lucky, your search produced one or more results related to your search.  The search query also scores the documents.  Those documents which fit best with your search query will have the highest score.  The second number returned by the search query is the length of the ASCII text document that formed the original metadata document, and upon which the index was created.
 <HR>
