 <HTML>
 
 <HEAD>
 <TITLE>FEDERAL GEOGRAPHIC DATA COMMITTEE </TITLE>
 <H1>FACILITIES WORKING GROUP </H1>
REVISED 26 January 1995 <p>

 <H3>Scope: </H3>
 <H4> 
	A Facilities Working Group will be established to work within the Federal 
Geographic Data Committee (FGDC) and with other non-Federal communities to 
enhance facility management.  A facility is an entity with location, 
deliberately established as a site for designated activities.  Facility 
Management involves the planning, operation, and maintenance of facilities to 
insure that they perform their intended purpose in an effective and efficient 
manner and in harmony with environmental and other socio-economic constraints. <P>
	The objectives of the Working Group will be to: promote standards of 
accuracy and currentness in facilities data which is financed in whole in part 
by Federal funds; exchange information on technological improvements for 
collecting facilities data; encourage the Federal and non-Federal community to 
identify and adopt standards and specifications for facilities data; and to 
promote the sharing of facilities data among Federal and non-Federal 
organizations. <P>
     A facility database might describe a factory, a military base, a college, 
a hospital, a power plant, a fishery, a national park, an office building, a 
space command center, or a prison.  The database for a complex facility may 
describe multiple functions or missions, multiple buildings, or even a county, 
town, or city. <P>
     The variety and breadth of a facility results in databases with a variety 
of themes or categories of information and as such, the Facilities Working 
Group is interested in the data standards being developed by other FGDC 
subcommittees and working groups.  The Facilities Working Group recognizes the 
need to coordinate with these other FGDC entities to develop standards for the 
more detailed, larger scale, and higher resolution data that are not currently 
a priority of other FGDC subcommittees, yet are required by the facilities 
community.  Since facility data will often be the most accurate and detailed 
data available for a geographic location, this data could represent a 
significant contribution to the National Geospatial Data "Framework".  The 
Facilities Working Group recognizes the need to coordinate with the Framework 
Working Group in this arena. <P>
     The Facilities Working Group will have specific responsibility for 
addressing data issues for data that is not currently represented by other 
FGDC subcommittees such as utilities (water, gas, electric, storm sewer, 
wastewater, industrial waste, telephone, radio, cable TV, satellite), 
environmental hazards (HTRW, land, water, air, and noise pollution), 
airspace safety, firing ranges, explosive ordnance safety, and training ranges. <P>
     Since facility management can involve processing and integrating high and 
low resolution data and large and small scale data, the Facilities Working 
Group recognizes its opportunity to be a link between the FGDC and other 
entities such as the National Institute for Building Sciences (NIBS) and the 
American Public Works Association (APWA). <P>
 </H4>

 <H3>Activities: </H3> <P>
 <h4>
Specific activities of the Working Group include: <P>

Promote the coordination of agencies' facilities related activities and 
exchange of facilities data and guidance, by formal and informal means. <P>

Collect and compile information on Federal agencies' facilities related data 
activities. <P>

Data for a specific facility can be created and maintained using multiple 
systems such as Geographic Information Systems (GIS), Computer-Aided Drafting 
and Design (CADD), Automated Mapping/Facilities Management (AM/FM), and Land 
Information Systems (LIS) and their associated databases.  Develop guidelines 
on integrating data created using these various technologies. <P>

Data sources for a specific facility can be in various resolutions.  Develop 
guidelines on integrating multiple resolution data sets for a single site. <P>

Develop a features and attribute register for facilities data that is not 
currently represented by other FGDC Subcommittees.  Develop this per the FGDC 
Process for Standards Development and also submit this to the Spatial Data 
Transfer Standard(SDTS)/Federal Information Processing Standard (FIPS) 173 Task 
Force for possible incorporation into the FIPS 173. <P>

A facilities database can contain 50 or more themes of data, all with varying 
resolution and accuracy.  The database may also contain sensitive data that 
should have controlled access.  Develop any additional guidance needed for 
documenting facilities data sets with the FGDC Content Standard for Digital 
Metadata. <P>

Support the development of SDTS/FIPS 173 profiles which will be suited to 
facilities data, such as SDTS CADD profiles. <P>

Work with the non-Federal community such as the public utility companies, 
county fire and rescue units, AM/FM International, the American Public Works 
Association (APWA), the American Society of Civil Engineers (ASCE), the American
 Architects Society, the National Institute for Building Sciences (NIBS), the 
Federal Facilities Council (FCC), the Urban and Regional Information Systems 
Association (URISA), and the American Institute of Architects (AIA). <P>
 </H4>

 <H3>Duration: </H3> <P>
 <H4>
The Facilities Working Group will operate for 1-2 years, or until a permanent 
management/coordination process for facilities data is established, such as an 
FGDC subcommittee.  <P>
 </H4>



 <H3>Linkages: </H3> <P>
 <H4>
The Facilities Working Group will have close ties with all FGDC subcommittees, 
working groups, and member agencies; National Institute of Standards and 
Technology (NIST); interested local and state governments; public utility 
companies; professional societies such as APWA, ASCE, and AM/FM International; 
NIBS; and the private sector.  <P>
 </H4>

 <H3>Agency lead: </H3> <P>
 <H4>
The Working Group shall be chaired by the U.S. Army Corps of Engineers.  The 
Corps of Engineers represents DoD's facilities/civil works interests to the 
FGDC and is also a member of the Tri-Service CADD/GIS Technology Center 
oversight group. The Center is responsible for the coordination of CADD and GIS
technologies throughout the DoD Installations and Facilities community and will 
provide critical support to this Working Group, especially in the area of 
standards. <P>
 </H4>
 <HR>
 <H4> <A HREF="http://fgdc.er.usgs.gov/fgdc.html">Return to FGDC Home Page </A> </H4> <p>

 <H4> <A HREF="../welcome.html">Return to USACE Geospatial Clearinghouse Title Page </A> </H4> <P>
 <HR>
Page owner:  <a href = "mailto:webmaster@corps_geo1.usace.army.mil">
webmaster@corps_geo1.usace.army.mil </a> <p>
