 <img src = "../images/castle.gif" alt = "USACE Home Page">

 <h3>
USACE Geospatial Data Server:<br>
Manual on how to submit and access data and metadata</h3>

<h1>
E. Accessing Corps geospatial data and metadata 
 </h1>

<b>
Version: 22 November 1996
 </b><br>
  <h3>
Table of contents
 </h3>

<dl>
<dd> <a href = "#metadata">E1. USACE metadata</a> 
 <dd>  <a href = "#access">E2. Accessing data via
          metadata: keyword search, image maps, USACE
          command list</a>
 <dd> <a href = "#ftp">E3. Accessing Corps metadata using
          anonymous ftp</a>
 </dl>

<strong>The data described in the metadata files produced by the US Army 
Corps of Engineers represent the results of data collection and processing 
for a specific US Army Corps of Engineers activity and indicates the general
existing conditions.  As such it is only valid for its intended use, 
content, time, and accuracy specifications.  The user is responsible
for the results of any application of the data for other than its intended
purpose.
 </strong> 
<p>
Please note that data and metadata files are currently being accepted on the Corps Geospatial Server. Read
<a href = "ht-submit.html">Section C</a> of this document for information about metadata submission procedures and  <a href = "ht-dsubmit.html">Section D</a> for information about data submission. 
<p>
 <strong>
 <a name = "metadata">
E1. USACE metadata</a>
</strong>
<br>
The USACE geospatial data and metadata available on the web include <I>collection metadata</I> and all other metadata. Collection metadata is a single metadata file that describes a series of related data files that are routinely collected by an agency. For example, the data may be hydrographic files which have been collected for 20 years. 
USACE Headquarters has created a series of templates of collection metadata files for USACE commands to edit or delete, as appropriate. Links to these are found under each command's data pages. 

<p>
Other metadata files may describe a unique data file or a unique collection of data files, i.e. a collection of data files that are not routinely collected by an agency. On the USACE Server these are called <I>detailed metadata</I>.

<p>
All metadata files name the Point of Contact for the data set described and state how the data can be obtained. In the future, there will be links from the metadata to data sets for data which is available on the Server. Commands will decide which of their data products to make available on the Server.

<p>
<strong>
<a name =  "access">
E2. Accessing data via metadata: keyword search, image maps, USACE command list</a>.
</strong>
<br>
There are four ways to search for data on the USACE Server. To determine is the data is appropriate for your use, you can access the corresponding metadata file and read about the specifications of the data. The four search tools include:

<ol>
<li> A WWW form to do a  keyword search, 
<li> Image maps,
<li> A textual list of USACE commands  and
<li> Anonymous ftp.
</ol>
<p>
Anonymous ftp will be described in the next section of this document.
There are links on the Server homepage to the textual 
<a href = "../org.direct.html">USACE command list</a> 
(<I>see</I> Locating USACE Metadata using a list of 
USACE Commands) and to the 
<a href = "../metadata.html">image maps</a> 
(<I>see</I> Locating USACE Metadata using maps). 
Both of these links lead to the
same command data pages. From the data pages, there are links 
to the command's collection and detailed metadata pages.
<p>
A link to a 
<a href = "query.html">keyword search form</a>
is also is available from the Server homepage (<I>see</I>
Search USACE and NSDI Clearinghouse metadata
databases using a form). The keyword 
search allows you to enter a keyword or keywords which 
describe the subject in which you are interested.
The search can be limited to metadata
 from only specific USACE commands.
The USACE geospatial metadata is spatially indexed.
This means that you can add geographic coordinates 
to the search statement, limiting the search to only the geographic area in 
which you are interested. Details of how to enter keywords
are found at the bottom of the keyword search form.
<p>
 <strong>
 <a name = "ftp">
E3. Accessing Corps metadata using anonymous ftp</a>
</strong>
 <br>
You also can get metadata or data by using anonymous  
ftp (file transfer protocol) originating from your local computer.
 This will allow you to download metadata or data
files to your computer. You do not need to have a Corps UPASS 
user id. Use your computer's ftp utility. 
 If you don't know how to use the ftp utility on your computer,
 you'll have to ask a knowledgeable neighbor or your desktop
 support team. 

<p>
The host computer you are ftp-ing to is
<dl>
 <dd><kbd>corps_geo1.usace.army.mil</kbd>
 </dl>

The login id is

<dl>
<dd><kbd>anonymous</kbd>
</dl>

and for a password you can use your email address.
<p>
 When you log on the anonymous ftp site you are at the top
of the Server ftp directory structure. There you will see the 
names <I>labs</I> and <I>foa</I> (field operating activities),
and acronyms for the divisions. Entering these directories will lead you
to directories of the subordinate commands which 
contain a metadata  and a geo_data directory.  The difficulty 
of using anonymous ftp is that if you do not  know exactly 
where to find what you want, you must browse around the 
directories seeking it. 
<p>
When you are done with the ftp session, close it and 
exit from the ftp software. If you stop 
communicating with the ftp site for some 
period of time during the ftp session,
you may be "timed out," i.e. you will not be connected 
to the Server anymore.  If this occurs you will have to 
ftp to the Server again.

<hr>
