<html>
<head>
<title>
USACE manual on how to submit and access data and metadata
</title>
</head>
 
<body>
<a name = "local-top"> </a>
||
 <a href = "#local-bottom">
Bottom of page</a>
||
<a href = "how-to.html">
How-to Manual</a>
||
 <a href = "../welcome.html#local-top">
USACE Geospatial Clearinghouse Title Page</a>
||
<hr>
 <img src = "../images/castle.gif" alt = "USACE Home Page">

 <h3>
USACE Geospatial Data Server:<br>
Manual on how to submit and access data and metadata </h3>

<h1>C.  Metadata submission to the Server </h1>

 <b>Version: 22 November 1996</b>
<p>

<h3>
Table of Contents
 </h3>


 <dl>
 <dd> <a href = "#access">C1. Accessing the Server for
metadata submission </a>

<ul>
<li> <a href = "../user-id1.html">Register to submit 
     metadata and data.</a> (Also see other requirements 
     in this section.)
</ul>
 
<dd> <a href = "#meta">C2. Metadata file format</a>
 <dd> <a href = "#filename">C3. Filename conventions</a>
 <dd> <a href = "#submit">C4. Submitting metadata to the Server</a>
 <dd> <a href = "#replace">C5. Replacing or deleting metadata files</a>
  </dl>

Please note that data and metadata files are currently being accepted on the Corps Geospatial Server. Read
<a href = "ht-dsubmit.html">Section D</a> of this document for information about data submission procedures.
Corps personnel and  non-Corps people can search, view and obtain data and metadata by browsing  the WWW site, WAIS keyword searches and  anonymous ftp.  See 
<a href = "ht-access.html">Section E</a> for more information on accessing data and metadata.
<p>
If you have questions about anything in this document, you can ask your GD&S POC. If  you need further assistance, please email your questions or comments to the Server webmaster at
 
 <dl>
 <dd>
<a href = "mailto:webmaster@corps_geo1.usace.army.mil">
webmaster@corps_geo1.usace.army.mil</a>
 </dl>

 <p>
 <b>
 <a name = "access">
C1. Accessing the Server for metadata submission
 </a>
 </b>
 <br>
Three steps are needed to get access to the Server for metadata submission.

 <p>
1. Inform the Geospatial Data and Systems (GD&S) POC for your organization that you  intend to submit metadata to the Server. The name and contact information for the GD&S POC of each USACE command is shown on the command's data page on the Server web site. You can get to a command's  data page via an
<a href = "../org.direct.html">alphabetical list</a>
or an 
<a href = "../metadata.html">image map</a>. A list of USACE GD&S POCs  is available for downloading in 
<a href = "ftp://corps_geo1.usace.army.mil/pub/gd_and_s/">
WordPerfect6.0 format</a> on the web site also. 
 
 <p>
2.  To put metadata files on the USACE Geospatial  Server you must get a Corps UPASS user id that is recognized by the Server.  This is the same UPASS user id that is recognized by the Server for data submission. The Corps standard UPASS system will be used for issuing and controlling user ids and passwords.  To get a UPASS user id, ask your UPASS administrator for a "UPASS user id on the Geospatial Metadata and Data Server on corps_geo1." To find out who your UPASS administrator is, contact your information management group.

 <p>
3.  The system administrator of the Geospatial Data Server must have your email address before the automatic metadata submission process will work. You can use the <a href = "../user-id1.html">Corps_geo1 Access Form</a> or email your email address with a message saying that you have requested access to the Server to

 <dl>
 <dd> 
<a href="mailto:webmaster@corps_geo1.usace.army.mil">
webmaster@corps_geo1.usace.army.mil</a>
 </dl>
<p>
 <b>
 <a name = "meta">
C2. Metadata file format
 </a>
 </b>
 <br>
All metadata files submitted to the Server should conform to the Federal Geographic Data Committee (FGDC) Standard for Digital Geospatial Metadata, published 8 June 1994.  This is in conformance with USACE Engineer Regulation 1110-1-8156. The FGDC Standard can be viewed in an HTML format at the URL
<p>
<dl>
<dd>
<a href = "http://geochange.er.usgs.gov/pub/tools/metadata/standard/">
http://geochange.er.usgs.gov/pub/tools/metadata/standard/</a>
</dl>
<p>
It also can be downloaded (ftped) in various file formats with the name
meta6894.<i>ext</i> where .<i>ext</i> is the filename extension of a 
particular file format type. The URL for downloading is
 
<p>
<dl>
<dd>
<a href = "ftp://www.fgdc.gov/pub/metadata/">
ftp://www.fgdc.gov/pub/metadata/</a>
</dl>
<p>
Metadata files should be in ASCII text format or they will be unreadable on the Server.
<p>
The Corps metadata generator software package, CORPSMET, creates metadata in the correct format. CORPSMET can be 
<a href = "ftp://corps_geo1.uasce.army.mil">downloaded</a>
from this site. Other GIS and metadata generator software packages also are available.
<p>
It is recommended that you check your metadata using the mp (metadata parser) formal metadata compiler created by Peter Schweitzer, USGS, which will tell you if your metadata file has formatting errors or field omissions. Descriptions of the files and the source code for the metadata compiler and its related programs are available at 
<a href = "http://geochange.er.usgs.gov/pub/tools/metadata">
http://geochange.er.usgs.gov/pub/tools/metadata</a> under the bullet
"A complier for formal metadata."
<p>
In the future, files will have to pass through this metadata parser as part of the USACE Server acceptance process. This will be necessary when the Server must change from WAIS to Isite indexing to comply with the National Spatial Data Clearinghouse standards. Three types of errors will cause the metadata file to be rejected, including unrecognized elements, misplaced elements, and missing elements. As explained by Mr. Schweitzer, "mp is extremely picky by design, and most metadata has some flaws.  The most recent
version of mp classifies errors as, in order of decreasing severity:
<p>
  unrecognized elements<br>
  misplaced elements<br>
  missing elements<br>
  superfluous elements<br>
  empty elements (missing values) <br>
  improper element values
<p>
It's my hope that this classification will help people put proper
perspective in their handling of the errors.  The Clearinghouse
won't work well with metadata that have unrecognized or misplaced
elements, and missing elements will make the metadata less useful,
but the other errors are probably more tolerable." (Personal  communication, Dec. 1996)
<p>
<b>
 <a name = "filename">
C3.  Filename conventions
 </a>
 </b>
 <br>
When the metadata file arrives at the Server, a script runs that uses the filename extension to determine how it will handle the file. Original metadata files should have the extension .met. Other extensions are used for files that are to replace other files (.rep) or to be deleted (.del) and for data files (.dat).  When you ftp the file to the Server you can make the name as long as you want and so can add the .met to the filename you used on your PC. All filenames should consist of a <b>continuous</b> string of characters which may include  numbers, letters, underscore ( _ ), hyphen (-), and dot ( . ). Other special characters should be avoided.
<p>
In the past, metadata filenames were changed as they were moved to the Server metadata storage area. (User-id, date and time were added to the original name.) This no longer occurs. The GD&S POCs and persons submitting metadata are responsible for keeping track of the filenames of the command's metadata. The filename will be needed if the metadata has to be replaced, updated or deleted in the future.  The filenames currently in a command's metadata directory can be seen by  using anonymous ftp to get to the command's metadata directory (see Section E, Accessing Corps geospatial data and metadata).

 <p>
 <b>
 <a name = "submit">
C4.  Submitting metadata to the Server
 </a>
 </b>
 <br>
To put a metadata file on the Geospatial Server, follow 
these steps.

 <p>
1. Plan your filename. Remember to use the .met
extension for metadata file submissions.
<p>
2. Use your computer's ftp utility. There are many variations of ftp software. It would be impossible to describe them all. If you don't know how to use the ftp utility on your computer, you'll have to ask a knowledgeable neighbor or your desktop support team. 

<p>
3. The host computer you are ftp-ing to is
<dl>
 <dd>corps_geo1.usace.army.mil
 </dl>

The login id and password you will use are your UPASS user id and password. When you have successfully ftp'ed to corps_geo1, you will be in your home directory on the Server. This is the only place on the Server where you can put files. 

 <p>
5. To submit the metadata file, you will use the <I>copy</I> or <I>put</I> function in your ftp software. 
You can submit multiple files during one session if you want to.
 
<p>
6. When you are done putting metadata on the Server, close the session and exit from the ftp software. If you stop communicating with the ftp site for some period of time during the ftp session,
you may be "timed out," i.e. you will not be connected to the Server anymore.  If this occurs you will have to ftp to the Server again.

 <p>
7. If a metadata submission is successfully processed you will receive an email message saying
so.  If the file is not successfully processed, you will receive an email message the next day stating this and explaining why it was not successfully processed..
 
 <p>
 <b>
 <a name = "replace">
C5. Replacing or deleting metadata files 
 </a>
 </b>
 <br>
To replace or delete a metadata file, you will need to
know the exact filename of the file to be replaced or 
deleted. You can use anonymous ftp to go to your
organization's metadata directory to look for the filename you need.
(Login procedures for anonymous ftp are 
different from the UPASS user id login.  Directions for logging into
anonymous ftp, listing filenames, and viewing ASCII files are given
below in Section E3, Accessing Corps metadata using 
anonymous ftp. ) If you are trying to replace or delete files that originally you did not put on the Server, you will have to contact the webmaster (webmaster@crrel.usace.army.mil) to become the owner of that file or set of files.
<p>
<u>To replace (or update) a metadata file</u>, have the replacement file ready on your local computer. The filename of the replacement file should be in the format

 <dl>
 <dd><I>filename(.met)</I>.rep
 </dl>
 
where  <i>filename(.met)</i> is the filename of the file to be replaced.  It will end with .met so the filename you type here will end with .met.rep. The extension .rep will cause the Server to replace the metadata file currently in your command's metadata directory with the file you just put in your home directory.
<p>
Ftp to the corps_geo1
computer as described in the directions given for submitting metadata 
(Section C4).  Use your UPASS user id and password to log in.  Then use the ftp utility <I>put</I> or <I>copy</I> function to put the file onto the Server. When you are done, close the ftp session and quit the ftp utility.
<p>
<u>To delete a metadata file</u>, first create a dummy file on your local
computer with the same filename as the name of the file you want to delete.  It doesn't matter what is in the dummy file. The dummy filename should be in the format
 
 <dl>
 <dd> <i> filename(.met)</i>.del
 </dl>

where <I>filename(.met)</i> is the name of the dummy file you created on your local computer 
<I>and</I> the filename of the file to be deleted.   It will end with .met so the filename will
end with .met.del. The extension .del will cause the Server to delete
the metadata file you have named.
<p>
Ftp to the Server as described 
above in the directions given above for submitting metadata
(Section C4).  Use
your UPASS user id and password to log in.  Then use the ftp utility <I>put</I> or <I>copy</I> function to put the dummyfile on the Server. Close your ftp session and quit the ftp utility.
<p>
As always, problems or questions can be address to your GD&S POC and then the webmaster.

<hr>
