 <HTML>
 <HEAD>
 <TITLE>Minutes from 08 Apr, 1996 </TITLE>
 <H1>Minutes </H1>
 </HEAD>

 <BODY>
Summary Report


 <H3>Federal Geographic Data Committee (FGDC)
Facilities Working Group Meeting 
8 April 1996 
 </H3>
 <H4>
Headquarters, U.S. Army Corps of Engineers (USACE)
Pulaski Building, Washington, DC
 </H4>


1)  Persons Attending:   <A HREF="./04-08-96.attatch1.html">Attendance roster. </A> <P> 

* See  <A HREF="./04-08-96.attatch2.html">agenda </A> <P>


2)  Update on FGDC Activities - M.K. Miles (USACE): 
 <UL>
	 <LI>The Steering Group will meet on 30 April in the main Interior Building and the primary agenda item is developing state councils and partnerships.
	 <LI>The Coordination Group has a questionnaire on state councils and partnerships to complete by 10 April.  This will be used to guide the discussions at the Steering Group meeting.  Mr. Miles provided a copy of the questionnaire and it is available on the FGDC server for those who are interested.  Any responses received after 10 April will be useful beyond the Steering Group meeting.  If you have data or resources that could help produce a more accurate 2000 Census please contact the Census Bureau reps on the FGDC.  The FGDC Coordination Group may sponsor a workshop on this.  Several members of the Coordination Group are working on the charters for the Subcommittees and Working Groups to ensure that the focus is on national and federal efforts as opposed to agency specific goals.   
	 <LI>The Standards Working Group will have an FGDC-wide meeting on 9 April from 1-4, Room 8222D, HQUSACE, 20 Massachusetts, Avenue, NW, Washington, DC.  The FGDC Subcommittee and Working Group Status Summary Report (It includes recommendations for improving the efficiency of the FGDC) will be discussed.
 </UL>

3)  Development of a Facility/Installation ID Code Standard (Group):
 <UL>
	 <LI>Mr. Ron Niemi (HQUSACE, Center for Public Works) said that the Installations Corporate Information Management (ICIM) definitions for facility, installation, and land tract that he presented at the last meeting will be used unless this FGDC Facilities Group recommends something else.  Ms Heather James from Calibre Systems (an ICIM contractor) gave a presentation on activity models used in the ICIM effort.  She suggested that the FGDC Facilities Working Group might want to use these models to ensure that they are considering all pertinent information in the pursuit of facilities data standards.  Ms James provided handouts for her presentation.
	 <LI>At the last meeting, the group thought that a matrix of agency use of facility and installation terminology would be useful in pursuing a Facility ID Code definition so the Chair prepared a  <A HREF="./04-08-96.attatch3.html">matrix </A> from input received from the members of the group.   Mr. Dave Catlin (EPA) said that EPA does not have the need to catagorize things any broader or more narrow than "facility."  EPA just puts a code on the feature and describes it.  This led to a discussion on Mr. Bruce Bargmeyer's (EPA)  recommendations for developing a Facility ID Code and the Group agreed with the approach, which is: 
	 <UL>
		 <LI>Use a non-intelligent identifier to give anything a unique identity.  In order to prevent agencies from having to redo existing coding schema, associate each facility ID with an  "Identifier Context" that describes existing codes.  Examples are GSA, state, FGDC, etc.  Agencies may choose to migrate to a Federal coding schema eventually but in the meantime we would just ask them to obtain one of our non-intelligent identifiers and equate it/link it with their existing identifier.  The National Institutes of Standards and Technology (NIST) might be interested in maintaining this ID Code register.
		 <LI>Have the ID point to a minimum and mandatory set of data elements about the facility.  Let agencies record any information beyond that mandatory set as well.  Examples are name, address, owner, location, and category of facility.  Category of facility could include the categories we are currently considering, i.e. installation, facility, landtrack, etc.  Mr. Bargmeyer said this would be consistent with ISO and ANSI approaches. The Group still thinks that a Facility ID Code Standard would improve data exchange within the facilities community.
	 </UL>
	 <LI>ACTION: A small group agreed to write a short proposal for a Facility ID Code Standard and present it at the next meeting (Dave Catlin, Bruce Bargmeyer (EPA), Kevin Backe (USACE), David Hammond (Coast Guard).  Bruce Bargmeyer agreed to take the lead on this and to contact Mr. Dan McHugh and Mr. Bruce Spear directly for input (these 2 group members had specific recommendations in the past about the ID Code Standard).  Send your ideas to Bruce Bargmeyer (Facility Working Group).
 </UL>

4)  Draft DoD Directive for EO 12906 Compliance (Penny Capps, HQUSACE):
 <UL>
	 <LI>Members of the Tri-Service CADD/GIS Technology Center Executive Working Group have drafted a DoD Directive to provide guidance on complying with EO 12906.  The purposes are to:
	 <UL>
		 <LI> Ensure consistent implementation within DoD
		 <LI> List those data sets that, per the Secretary of Defense, will have restricted release to the public because of threats to national security
		 <LI> Define the process for obtaining a waiver from the Secretary of Defense for complying with EO 12906.
	 </UL>
The Chair asked for advice from the Facilities Working Group on developing a list of data themes related to a facility that should have restricted release to the public, i.e. power grids, weapons storage sheds, etc.  If the data sets are already restricted, provide the public law or act that states this. The Chair will provide a copy of this directive to the Facilities Working Group once it has been coordinated with the Defense Mapping Agency and other DoD agencies.
	 <LI>ACTION: Recommend to the chair any facility-related data themes that should be waived from EO 12906 compliance and cite any public laws or acts that exist that restrict release of data to the public (Facilities Working Group).
 </UL>	




5)  Proposal of Some Tri-Service Spatial Data Standards (TSSDS) Entity Classes as FGDC Facilities Working Group Standards (Miles):
 <UL>
	 <LI>At the last meeting the Facilities Group agreed to review the TSSDS Utilities, Buildings, Improvements, Communications, and Environmental Hazards entity classes and recommend changes or recommend that these sections be initiated into the FGDC standards development process.  Some members stated that had reviewed portions of some of these entities.  Mr. Miles suggested that we might make more progress if we start with one entity such as Utilities.
	 <LI>ACTION: Review the TSSDS Utilities entity.  Be prepared to propose any changes required to meet your agency needs or to propose the TSSDS Utility entity as is, as an FGDC standard. (GROUP).  
 </UL>

6)  Proposal of the TSSDS Structure as an FGDC Standard - (Miles/Ed Riegelmann, Tri-Service CADD/GIS Technology Center):
 <UL>
	 <LI>Mr. Miles distributed the proposal that went forward to the FGDC Standards Working Group on adopting the TSSDS structure.  This proposal was revised from the last version that the Facilities Working agreed on.  The Standards Working Group said it was more appropriate for USACE to be the proposing FGDC agency and the Standards Working Group would use the Tri-Service Center as a subcontractor if approved by the FGDC.  The focus of the proposal is to use the TSSDS structure and the interactive approach (Microsoft Access) as a tool to assist FGDC subcommittees in developing data content standards in a consistent format and to integrate these standards on one CD for distribution to the public.  Mr. Riegelmann gave a demo of this interactive tool and structure and said he would be giving the same demo at the FGDC-wide meeting on 9 April.
 </UL>

7) Misc:
 <UL>
	 <LI>The American Planning Association (APA) conference is 13-17 April in Kissimmee, FL and the first APA Federal Planning Division (FPD) conference will be held 17-19 April in Kissimmee.  The Facilities Working Group Alternate Chair will give a presentation on the FGDC, Facilities Working Group, and EO 12906 at the FPD conference.
 </UL>

8)  Next Meetings:
 <UL>
	 <LI>The next three meetings will be 13 May, 17 June, and 15 July from 1-4 in Room 8222D of the Pulaski Building, 20 Massachusetts Avenue, NW, Washington, DC. 
 </UL>

 </BODY>
 </HTML>
