 <HTML>
 <HEAD>
 <TITLE>Minutes from 13 May, 1996 </TITLE>
 <H1>Minutes </H1>
 </HEAD>

 <BODY>
Summary Report


<H3>Federal Geographic Data Committee (FGDC)
Facilities Working Group Meeting
17 June 1996 
</H3>
<H4>
Headquarters, U.S. Army Corps of Engineers (USACE)
Pulaski Building, Washington, DC
</H4>


1)  Persons Attending:  <A HREF="./06-17-96.attatch1.html">Attendance roster.</A> <P>

* See <A HREF="./06-17-96.attatch2.html">agenda.</A> <P>


2)  Update on FGDC Activities - M.K. Miles (USACE): 
<UL>
<LI>The Steering Group  met on 12 June.  Secretary Babbitt was the keynote speaker at the May ESRI Users Conference and he voiced his support of the use of GIS and other geospatial data related technologies.  Ms Nancy Tosta is leaving the FGDC to work for the Pugent Sound Regional Council. 
Mr.  Mark Schaffer, the Assistant Deputy Undersecretary for Water Resources within DOI, asked that FGDC Steering Group members contact him with discussion items, recommendations on FGDC focus, etc.  The DOI budget examiner at the Office of Management and Budget, Mr. Bruce Baird,  suggested being prepared to defend GIS and geospatial data related costs within your agency budgets, as the Departments of Interior and Agriculture are being questioned on the Hill.  
<LI>The Coordination Group held a meeting on 11 June.  The FGDC has recognized approximately 11 State NSDI coordinating councils and hopes to conduct some FGDC Coordination Group meetings outside of Washington, DC so that more state reps can participate.  The Competitive Cooperative Agreements Program (CCAP) winners for FY97 have been selected but not notified.  This program is entering its third year and awards approximately $1M to non-Federal agencies to develop the NSDI.  The FGDC has 1 more month to review the Cadastral Content Standard.  It will not go out for another public review.  
<LI>The Standards Working Group (SWG) held a meeting on 11 June.  The Tri-Service CADD/GIS Technology Center is working on the prototype of the integrated FGDC standards model. The Center will integrate the appropriate parts of the following data content and classification standards: Base Carto (DLG-E), Vegetation, Cadastral, and Wetlands.  Some large scale features of the TSSDS will also be included to demonstrate the ability of the tool to flag potential overlaps.  Some agencies wanted to include non-spatial information and the decision was made to stick with geospatial data only for the prototype. 
<UL>
<LI>During the 17 June Facilities Working Group meeting, Mr Bargmeyer (EPA) commented that the TSSDS and X3L8 efforts need to be coordinated at some point in the future.  He stated that the efforts seem compatible.
</UL>
</UL>


3)  Draft Proposal of Utilities Content Standard (Penny Capps, USACE and Harold Smith, Tri-Service CADD/GIS Technology Center):
<UL>
<LI>Ms Capps presented the <A HREF="./06-17-96.attatch3.html">draft proposal</A> for an FGDC Utilities Data Content Standard that Mr. Kevin Backe (USACE) wrote.  She explained that this proposal will be submitted to the FGDC Standards Working Group to indicate the intent to develop a standard.  This enables the Standards Working Group to track the standards that are being developed, avoid duplicative standards development efforts, etc.  Mr. Rik Wiant (USACE) asked that the scope be modified to include a list or description of the utilities addressed by the standard.  Ms Capps said that she will edit the proposal as requested in the hopes of submitting it to the FGDC Standards Group at their 9 July meeting.  If she receives conflicting requests for edits she will bring the proposal back to the next Facilities meeting to resolve them before submitting to the Standards Group.
<LI>Mr. Smith briefed the TSSDS Utilities entity set using an interactive Microsoft Access application.  He explained that we should remove the implementation specific content (coverage name, concatenated names, etc.) prior to submitting the standard to the Standards Working Group.  This information is supplied so that the Army, Navy, Air Force installations can immediately implement the TSSDS in ARC/INFO, MGE, Microstation, and AutoCAD environments.  Implementation information can be provided as a bonus or option but not as a Federal standard.  Mr. Wiant asked if cable TV and other communication features are included in the TSSDS entity set.  Mr. Smith said that information is under the Communications entity.  Ms Carolyn Davis (FEMA) asked if this entity set includes oil refineries.  Mr. Smith said it does not and there are a few other such features that are not included in utilities but probably could be included in the TSSDS Buildings entity set.  He suspects that the user is probably only interested in the location or footprint of the refinery.  Mr. Smith said that to facilitate the review of the Utilities entity set he will provide the IDEF Model of the TSSDS to the Facilities Working Group.  This FIPS model will illustrate which features are included in which entity set, etc.  Captain Brodt (NIH) stated that since the current content is fairly complete and developed by subject matter experts he probably can not offer any additional information to incorporate.  However, he believes his role will be in the adjudication of comments.
<UL>
<LI>ACTION: Submit comments on the draft proposal to Ms Capps by 5 July (Facilities Working Group).
<LI>ACTION: Modify the proposal (Ms Capps) and submit at the 9 July Standards Working Group meeting (Mr. Backe).	
<LI>ACTION: Review the Utilities Entity Set and provide comments to Mr. Smith or bring to next meeting (Facilities Working Group).
<LI>ACTION: Remove the implementation specific content from the Utilities entity set and bring this version (digital and paper) to the 15 July Facilities Working Group meeting (Harold Smith).
<LI>ACTION: Provide the group with the IDEF model of the TSSDS at an August or September meeting (Harold Smith). 
</UL>
</UL>



4)  Draft Proposal for Environmental Hazards Content Standard (Penny Capps, USACE and Harold Smith Tri-Service CADD/GIS Technology Center):
<UL>
<LI>Ms Capps presented the <A HREF="./06-17-96.attatch4.html">draft proposal</A> for an FGDC Environmental Hazards Data Content Standard that Mr. Kevin Backe (USACE) wrote.  Several people commented that the Scope needs to be more descriptive and Mr. Dave Catlin (EPA) said he would provide comments on this.  Ms Capps said that she will edit the proposal as requested in the hopes of submitting it to the FGDC Standards Group at their 9 July meeting.  If she receives conflicting requests for edits she will bring the proposal back to the next Facilities meeting to resolve them before submitting to the Standards Group.
<LI>The Environmental Hazards Entity Set was briefed in great detail at the last meeting so there were not many questions.  Mr. Smith said that TSSDS 1.6 should be available in October and will include a much more robust environmental hazards entity set than the current version 1.4 (he is still accepting comments on 1.4).  He would like to wait until version 1.6 is complete and then prepare an implementation-free copy for review.  Otherwise he would remove this info from 1.4 and have to do it again 2 months from now for version 1.6.   Mr. Bruce Bargmeyer (EPA) said this was okay with him because it would take a couple of months to schedule a review of this content standard.  Mr. Al Lew (NASA) said this would give the group time to work through the standards development process on the utilities entity set.  Mr. Lew also commented that the National Institute of Building Sciences (NIBS) has some environmental work groups and we should notify them of our standards development plans.

<LI>ACTION: Submit comments on the draft proposal to Ms Capps by 5 July (Facilities Working Group).
<LI>ACTION: Modify the proposal (Ms Capps) and submit at the 9 July Standards Working Group meeting (Mr. Backe).
<LI>ACTION: Review the Environmental Hazards Entity Set and provide comments to Mr. Smith or bring to next meeting (Facilities Working Group).
<LI>ACTION: Remove the implementation specific content from the version 1.6 Environmental Hazards entity set and provide to the Facilities Working Group at an October/November meeting (Harold Smith).
<LI>ACTION: Provide the group with the IDEF model of the TSSDS at an August/September meeting (Harold Smith). 
<LI>ACTION: Coordinate with NIBS on development of this standard (Ms Capps).
</UL>

5)  Development of a Unique Identification Number (UIN) Standard for Facilities (Bruce Bargmeyer, EPA):
<UL>
<LI>Mr. Bargmeyer said that he has not received any comments on the UIN paper he presented at the last meeting.  He volunteered to prepare a proposal on this to submit to the FGDC Standards Working Group.  Mr. Bargmeyer distributed a list of data elements that EPA tracks for each facility.  He asked that the group provide him comments or bring comments to the next meeting on modifications to this list.  Ms Capps commented that some elements were data elements and some were metadata elements.  Mr. Bargmeyer said this needs to be addressed. Ms Capps said she would invite Mr. Domaratz, FGDC Project Manager for Framework, to a future meeting so that he could discuss the Framework concept for UINs (Mr. Domaratz has met with the Facilities Group on this topic but there have been a lot of new developments since that time).  We will also need to resurrect our discussions on some sort of typing structure (facility, installation, land tract, network, etc.) so that people know multiple facilities can be associated with an installation, etc.  
<LI>ACTION: Prepare a proposal to submit to the FGDC Standards Working Group for a Unique Identification Number Standard for Facilities.  Provide it at the 15 July Facilities meeting for review (Mr. Bargmeyer).
<LI>ACTION: Send comments on the UIN Standard Paper to Mr. Bargmeyer  (Facilities Working Group).  
<LI>ACTION: Provide comments to Mr. Bargmeyer on the Data Elements to track for facilities or bring them to the next meeting (Facilities Working Group).  
</UL>

5)  Misc.:   
<UL>
<LI>Mr. Wiant asked if anyone could explain the relationship between the FGDC Metadata Standard and the Government Information Locator Service (GILS).  Ms Capps explained that the GILS standard does accommodate geospatial data and the Metadata Standard adopted those elements and expanded on them.  So the 2 standards are in harmony.  <A HREF="mailto:btolar@usgs.gov">Mr. Billy Tolar</A> is the project manager for metadata.
</UL> 

6)   Next Meeting: 
<UL>
<LI>The next meeting will be 15 July from 1-4 in Room 8222D of the Pulaski Building, 20 Massachusetts Avenue, NW, Washington, DC. 
</UL>
</BODY>
</HTML>
