 <HTML>
 <HEAD>
 <TITLE>Minutes from 14 Feb, 1996 </TITLE>
 <H1>Minutes </H1>
 </HEAD>

 <BODY>
Summary Report


 <H3>Federal Geographic Data Committee (FGDC)
Facilities Working Group Meeting 
14 February 1996 
 </H3>
 <H4>
Headquarters, U.S. Army Corps of Engineers (USACE) <BR>
Pulaski Building, Washington, DC
 </H4>


1)  Persons Attending:   <A HREF="./02-14-96.attatch1.html">Attendance roster </A> <P>

* See  <A HREF="./02-14-96.attatch2.html">agenda </A> <P>


2)  Update on FGDC Activities - Penny Capps (USACE): 
 <UL>
	 <LI>The FGDC Coordination Group decided that the Facilities Working Group has been moved from ad hoc status to permanent status.
	 <LI>The FGDC Coordination Group agreed to form an ad hoc group to address standards for Land Cover.
	 <LI>The American Planning Association briefed the Coordination Group on their Federally funded efforts to create data standards for Land Use.
	 <LI>The Historical Working Group will have a meeting on March 7 to revitalize itself.
	 <LI>Lots of activity regarding the Metadata Standard.  The FGDC funded the Mitre Corporation to evaluate software that supposedly creates FGDC compliant Metadata Standard.  They will prepare a report on this by mid-year.  The International Standards Organization (ISO) is investigating the FGDC Metadata Standard as an ISO standard.  There will be a technical meeting in Denver during the week of 19 Feb to discuss potential revisions to the Metadata Standard, definition of a "core" set of elements,  and other things that need to happen to make the standard more useable.
	 <LI>The Clearinghouse Working Group has a paper on its FGDC Homepage titled, "What it Means to be a Clearinghouse Node."  Comments were due to the FGDC Clearinghouse Group by 20 Feb.
	 <LI>Contractors have delivered their final version of the FGDC Subcommittee and Working Group Status Summary Report (It includes recommendations for improving the efficiency of the FGDC). This was distributed at the meeting and is available from the FGDC Standards Working Group Homepage.  The Standards Working Group will correct any mistakes but will not be sending this back to the contractor for other revisions.  The Standards Working Group is trying to reschedule the FGDC-wide meeting to discuss this report for 9 April from 1-4, Room 8222D, HQUSACE, 20 Massachusetts, Avenue, NW, Washington, DC.
	 <UL>
		 <LI>ACTION: Review the report, especially references to the Facilities Working Group, and make sure the information is correct.  As this is already available on the Web, provide comments to Facilities Working Group Chair immediately (Group).
	 </UL>
	 <LI>Mr. Bruce Spear (Bureau of Transportation Statistics) said that as chair of the Ground Transportation Subcommittee he has been revising the charter for that group and has addressed the relationship between the Facilities Working Group and the Ground Transportation Subcommittee.  He stated that his subcommittee is interested in transportation features and connectivity of these features but not necessarily in the representation of those features (points, lines, polygons).  He recognized the Facilities Working Group as having responsibility for the detailed engineering and facility related information about certain transportation features.  He hopes that both groups can work together to collapse the detailed Facilities information into a Transportation/centerline type of product and to overlay the Transportation network data on the Facilities maps.  The Facilities Working Group agreed with this relationship.
 </UL>

3)  Proposal of TSSDS as an FGDC Facilities Working Group Standard - Kevin Backe (USACE):
 <UL>
	 <LI> Mr. Backe distributed a draft  <A HREF="./02-14-96.attatch3.html">proposal </A> for the Tri-Service Spatial Data Standards (TSSDS) to be accepted as an FGDC standard.  The proposal suggests that the TSSDS be the integrator of all FGDC standards plus include additional larger-scale information that the facilities community is interested in.  The TSSDS:
	 <UL>
		 <LI>Would be reformatted to remove agency specific information
		 <LI>Would emphasize that although there are implementations of this standard available for the vendor platforms used by the Tri-Service community, that this is not an FGDC endorsement of those platforms
		 <LI>Would provide a structure for all FGDC standards and all geospatial data of various resolutions to be bundled into one standard for use by federal, local, state, academic, and private agencies.
	 </UL>
	The Tri-Service Center would be used to accomplish this work and to create a CD.  The subcommittees and working groups remain the owners of their standards and they, not the Center, would be responsible for resolving problems between standards.  The Group agreed with the proposal concept and will provide comments on the content.
	 <LI>ACTION:   Provide comments to Mr. Backe by 1 March (Group).
 </UL>


4)  Definition of Facility/Installation - (Group):
 <UL>  
	 <LI>The Group decided that it needed firm definitions of Facility and Installation in order to promulgate an ID Code Standard on this type of data.  Some  <A HREF="./02-14-96.attatch4.html">definitions </A> the Group had considered were distributed.  Mr. Ron Niemi (USACE) said that the DoD is close to making a decision on these definitions for inclusion in the Defense Data Dictionary System (DDDS).  Mr. Niemi would like to take a Facilities Working Group proposal to the DoD meetings so that any definitions put in the DDDS would be useable by the rest of the Federal Government.  He distributed candidate definitions (Attachment 5) and said DoD found the FIPS definition of Facility inadequate and there is no FIPS definition of an Installation.  The discussion was overcome by the discussion on the development of an ID Code Standard, which is why the group thought it needed succinct definitions in the first place.  
	 <LI>ACTION: Everyone be prepared to continue this discussion, i.e. bring your ideas on installation and facility definitions.
 </UL>

5)  Development of a Facility/Installation ID Code Standard (Group): 
 <UL>
	 <LI>The Group is still struggling with this plan.  Mr. Spear expressed concern that there were already some accepted Facility codes in place for things like airports and he thought that agencies that maintain these codes would not be willing to tack on additional codes to fit into some grand coding registry.  Mr. Dan McHugh (NY City Transit) sited instances where he would find these codes useful, i.e. locating and accessing facility data, cross referencing data sets, etc.  This discussion went on for quite some time with no resolution.  Members who had worked on the subgroup to define this effort were not at the meeting so the group decided to readdress the problem at the next meeting.
	 <LI>ACTION: Be prepared to defend your position on this topic, we need to reach some consensus (Group)!
 </UL>

6)  Status of SDTS CADD Profile and Tri-Service Spatial Data Standards :
 <UL>
	 <LI>Mr. Riegelmann has a report on CADD elements needed for an SDTS CADD Profile and will provide it to interested Facility Working Group members..
	 <LI>ACTION: Tell Mr. Riegelmann you want to review this report (Group).
 </UL>

7)  Upcoming Conferences: 
 <UL>
	 <LI>The AM/FM International Conference is 24-27 March in Seattle, WA.  
	 <LI>The American Planning Association (APA) conference is 13-17 April in Kissimmee, FL and the first APA Federal Planning Division (FPD) conference will be held 17-19 April in Kissimmee.
	 <UL>
		 <LI>The Facilities Working Group Chair will give a presentation on the FGDC, Facilities Working Group, and EO 12906 at the FPD conference.
	 </UL>
 </UL>

8)  Next Meeting: 
 <UL>
	 <LI>The next meeting will be 11 March from 1-4 in room 7233 of the Pulaski Building, 20 Massachusetts Avenue, NW, Washington, DC.  
	 <LI>The Group might be willing to set the year's meetings for certain Monday afternoons from 1-4 but did not have time to resolve this at the meeting.
	 <LI>ACTION: Be prepared to discuss: 
	 <UL>
		 <LI>Definition of facility and installation
		 <LI>Development of an facility/installation ID Code Standard
		 <LI>TSSDS as an FGDC standard
		 <LI>Calendar for the year (Group).
	 </UL>
 </UL>

 </BODY>
 </HTML>
