 <HTML>
 <HEAD>
 <TITLE>Minutes from 21 October, 1996 </TITLE>
 <H1>Minutes </H1>
 </HEAD>

 <BODY>
Summary Report

 <H3>Federal Geographic Data Committee (FGDC)
Facilities Working Group Meeting 
21 December 1995 
 </H3>
 <H4>
Headquarters, U.S. Army Corps of Engineers (USACE) <BR>
Pulaski Building, Washington, DC
 </H4>

1)  Persons Attending:   <A HREF="./12-21-95.attatch1.html>Attendance roster </A>  <P>

* See attached  <A HREF="12-21-95.attatch2.html>agenda  </A>
 <P>


2)  Update on FGDC Activities - M.K. Miles, Penny Capps (USACE): 
 <UL>   
	 <LI>There will be an FGDC-wide meeting on 16 January from 1-4 at the USGS Auditorium in Reston, VA to discuss the FGDC Subcommittee and Working Group Status Summary Report (this was prepared by several contractors and distributed at several Facilities Working Group meetings). * Due to the furlough and inclement weather, this meeting was cancelled and has not been rescheduled.
	 <LI>The next FGDC Steering Group meeting will be held 9 January from 10-12 at the Main Department of Interior building.
	 <LI>The FGDC has new color coordinated folders and fact sheets that are useful when briefing coworkers on the FGDC.  You can obtain these at no charge by calling Ms Jennifer Snyder at 703-648-5514.
 </UL>

3)  Miscellaneous Facility Working Group Business - Penny Capps (USACE): <BR>
 <UL>
	 <LI>Minutes are available on the USACE Clearinghouse node (http://corps_geo1.usace.army.mil/FGDC/welcome.html)  and are linked to the FGDC homepage.  The Facilities Working Group membership list is on the server, with hot E-mail addresses of the members.  
	 <UL>
		 <LI>ACTION:  If you have not done so already, please E-mail, phone, or fax the chair your preference for either continuing to receive hardcopy minutes via postal mail or accessing them on the Facilities Working Group homepage (Facilities Working Group).
	 </UL>

	 <LI>Ms Capps attended GIS/LIS '95 in Nashville, TN in November and as a result added a few more non-Federal members to the Facilities Working Group.

	 <LI>Ms Capps had not completed a proposal to the FGDC for a Facility ID Standard.
	 <UL>

		 <LI>ACTION: Prepare a straw man based on the new Installation and Facility concept discussed at the meeting and present at the next meeting (Capps).
	 </UL>

	 <LI>The effort of the National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) and the U.S. Army Construction Engineering and Research Laboratory (CERL) to develop a facility ID code standard is based on existing Army codes.  The 2 agencies have had to map between a lot of existing codes and are interested in the Facilities Working Group proposal to develop a standard.
	
	 <LI>Ms Capps distributed draft copies of,  FGDC Facilities Working Group  <A HREF="./12-21-95.attatch3.html>1995 Accomplishments </A> and  FGDC Facilities Working Group  <A HREF="./12-21-95.attatch5.html">1996 Work Plan </A>.
	 <UL>
		 <LI>ACTION: Review and comment by next meeting (Facilities Working Group).
	 </UL>
 </UL>

4)  Status of SDTS CADD Profile and Tri-Service Spatial Data Standards - Ed Riegelmann (Tri-Service CADD/GIS Technology Center): <BR>
 <UL>
	 <LI>There are 3 steps to the contracted SDTS CADD Profile development and the contractors are in the middle of step 2.  The steps are:  <P>
	 <UL>
		 <LI>create/review a list of elements that need to be handled by a profile
		 <LI>create/review a list of SDTS elements that will handle the CADD elements
		 <LI>compare the lists to identify what will need to be developed.
	 </UL> <P>

	A final report is due in May with recommendations for the next steps.  Microstation and AutoCad represent 95% of the world's CADD market and since these product vendors are performing the SDTS CADD Profile work, we should get a reliable and useful report. <BR>
	Mr. Jerry Lenczowski (DMA) said that a CADD Profile could help DMA move from the world view to the bird's eye view and he will be glad to provide instances of phenomena that need to be handled by the CADD Profile to support the 3-D modeling/simulation community.
	 <UL>
		 <LI>ACTION:  Mr. Riegelmann will continue to provide status reports as well as the final report for the Facilities Working Group to review (Riegelmann).  Messrs Riegelmann and Lenczowski to coordinate on CADD elements (Riegelmann and Lenczowski).
	 </UL>

	 <LI>Messrs Riegelmann and Kevin Backe (USACE) are preparing a proposal that the Tri-Service Spatial Data Standards (TSSDS), or portions of it, be accepted as an FGDC standard.  They are also reformatting the TSSDS into the pieces that each FGDC subcommittee or working group will need to review, removing agency specific information, etc.  Mr. Riegelmann provided updates on the TSSDS as follows:
	 <UL>
		 <LI>There will be a March mid-release with some fixes but no change of content
		 <LI>DoD will adopt the TSSDS under its Corporate Information Management pillar which is one part of a huge DoD business process engineering effort
		 <LI>Canadians and the U.S. are thinking of proposing the TSSDS as an International Standard.
	
		 <LI>ACTION:  Messrs Riegelmann and Backe to present the proposal and reformatted TSSDS to the Facilities Working Group as soon as possible for approval (Riegelmann and Backe).
	 </UL>
 </UL>

5)  Definition of Facility - Group:  
 <UL>
	 <LI>The group agreed that it needed a tighter definition of  <A HREF="./12-21-95.attatch6.html>"Facility" </A> before it could develop a Facility ID Code Standard (Attachment 5).  The group could not figure out how to tighten the existing definition because facility really does include everything and groups of things. Discussions moved to defining "Installation" instead which seems to have solved some but not all problems.  Mr. Dan McHugh (NY City Transit Authority) provided diagrams of various plant components associated with transportation as an example of what some people consider a facility or an installation/networked facility.
	 <LI>The result of the discussion was that an Installation is a group or network of facilities and the Facilities Working Group should maintain a Registry for Installation IDs and develop some rules and guidelines for Facility IDs.   This would provide, " a big box to put big things (like installations) in and a smaller box to put small stuff (like facilities) in (Mr. McHugh)."  Standardizing on the Installation IDs would enable us to share data and agreeing upon rules/guidelines for facility IDs would give agencies the flexibility they need to assign codes.  Mr. Wiant reminded the group that this is sort of what the Army does and was an acceptable model to the Special Interest Group that investigated this topic for us.
	 <LI>Installations and facilities are things that are stable and not moveable and can be seen from the air or underground.  This excludes mobile things that should really be considered as equipment and excludes the insides of structures or buildings (Mr. McHugh and Mr. Ron Niemi).
	 <LI>We could start with a domain of installations that are of national scope, assign numbers to them, and then let each proponent/sponsoring agency determine the numbers for facilities inside the installations (Mr. Tom Conry).  As it turns out, the FGDC Cadastral Subcommittee has a domain of such things in its Cadastral Content Standard (Ms. Capps).
	 <LI>ACTION: Everyone be prepared to continue this discussion, i.e. bring your ideas on installation and facility definitions that would be appropriate for the proposed heirachical concept (Group)! <P>

 </UL>

6)  Miscellaneous - Group: 
 <UL>
	 <LI>Mr. Rik Wiant (USACE) said that the American Planning Association will meet 13 April in Orlando and there will be a follow on meeting from 17-19 April of the Federal Planning Division.  He hopes to have a TSSDS workshop, FGDC metadata workshop, and an open forum of the Facilities Working Group.   He will bring more information on the conferences to the next meeting.

 </UL>

7) Next Meeting: The next meeting will be 14 February from 1-4 in room 1225 of the Pulaski Building, 20 Massachusetts Avenue, NW, Washington, DC.
</DOC>
