 <HTML>
 <HEAD>
 <TITLE>Minutes from 11 Mar, 1996 </TITLE>
 <H1>Minutes </H1>
 </HEAD>

 <BODY>

Summary Report


 <H3>Federal Geographic Data Committee (FGDC)
Facilities Working Group Meeting 
11 March 1996 
 </H3>
 <H4>
Headquarters, U.S. Army Corps of Engineers (USACE)
Pulaski Building, Washington, DC
 </H4>


1)  Persons Attending:   <A HREF="./03-11-96.attatch1.html">Attendance roster </A> <P> 

* See  <A HREF="./03-11-96.attatch2.html">agenda </A> <P>


2)  Update on FGDC Activities - M.K. Miles/Penny Capps (USACE):
 <UL> 
	 <LI>The Steering Group received a briefing on the National Imagery Agency, which is to be created this Fall.  This new agency is to be created by combining several national imagery offices and the Defense Mapping Agency.  "National" in the title indicates the varied customer base.  The Department of Interior, NASA, etc. will not be included because the focus of this new group is classified image assets.  
	 <LI>The Clearinghouse Working Group had a meeting of experts in the Clearinghouse community a couple of weeks ago to discuss the future of the Clearinghouse and the Metadata standard.  Two key discussion items were the move by FGDC from WAIS to ISITE and the inclusion of sgml tags in metadata files.  Apparently ISITE will provide more capabilities and will be maintained more so than WAIS and the sgml tags will provide for more effective searching and browsing.  Things might be in place for this to happen in 1QFY97. 
	 <LI>The FGDC Subcommittee and Working Group Status Summary Report (It includes recommendations for improving the efficiency of the FGDC) will be discussed at an FGDC-wide meeting on 9 April from 1-4, Room 8222D, HQUSACE, 20 Massachusetts, Avenue, NW, Washington, DC.
 </UL>

3)  Definition of Facility/Installation - (Group):  
 <UL>
	 <LI>The Group decided that it needed a firm definition of Facility and Installation in order to promulgate an ID Code Standard on this type of data.  Mr. Ron Niemi (USACE) presented the definitions that will be included in the Defense Data Dictionary System (DDDS) unless he tells DOD that there is another set of Federal definitions (from the Facilities Working Group) that should be used.  He said that DoD found the FIPS definition of Facility inadequate and there is no FIPS definition of an Installation.  Mr. Dave Catlin (EPA) said they use the term "facility" but not "Installation" and are working to define sub-components of a facility and might use the term "sub-facility." However, they could probably map to another set of terms if the appropriate hierarchy was in place.  Mr. Al Lew (NASA) said they are revising their directives on definitions of facility and installation and this discussion is timely.  The Facilities Group thought the definitions were simple and flexible enough to either use or map to but would like to run through a short exercise to confirm this.  Mr. Dan McHugh (NY Transit) distributed a proposed set of terms and hierarchy using transit data as an example.  Mr. McHugh used a "sandwich" analogy to describe what the Facilities Working Group might want to standardize.  We would standardize on the meat of the sandwich and that would be terms like installation and facility.  The top piece of bread would be networks of installations that could be collapsed down, for example, into a network for national transportation use.  Even higher would be some sort of non-geospatial data that would be used for corporate planning purposes.  The bottom piece of bread would be sub-components of a facility that would be too numerous and controversial to deal with, such as manholes or telephone poles. 
	 <LI>ACTION: By 1 April, members should provide the Chair with comments on the  <A HREF="./03-11-96.attatch5.html">DOD and NY Transit terminology/hierarchy for facility and installation </A>.  Agencies may provide this input as an Excel spreadsheet, Word Perfect or Word Document, via email, or fax.  Include examples of terms, terms you use that won't/will map into the suggested terminology/hierarchy (GROUP).
 </UL>

4)  Development of a Facility/Installation ID Code Standard (Group):
 <UL>
	 <LI>The Group still thinks that this would improve data exchange within the facilities community and that the first step is to finalize some terminology/hierarchy as explained in item 3 above.  Mr. Lew said that NASA does not have a NASA-wide convention for numbering and identifying facilities and installations and that they are interested in this concept.
 </UL>


5)  Proposal of the Tri-Service Spatial Data Standards (TSSDS) as an FGDC Facilities Working Group Standard - Miles, Harold Smith (Tri-Service CADD/GIS Technology Center):
 <UL>
	 <LI>At the last Facilities meeting, the Group agreed to forward a proposal to the FGDC Standards Working Group for using the TSSDS as the integrator of all FGDC content standards and to standardize on some large scale/detailed features and attributes in a variety of thematic categories.  Mr. Miles updated the Group on some recent discussions he had with members of the Standards and Coordination Groups.  The latest proposal suggests that the TSSDS structure be adopted by the FGDC for developing content standards and that the TSSDS be used to integrate all FGDC content standards.  It would be the responsibility of the Standards Working Group, not the Facilities Working Group, and the Tri-Service Center to coordinate this.  The Subcommittees would still be the developer and authority on the content of the standard - the Center would just be used to bundle all these FGDC standards into one comprehensive package and in one format.  This should be a huge step towards identifying overlaps and for promoting the FGDC standards in the non-Federal geospatial data community.  This will be discussed at future Coordination and Standards meetings.
	 <LI>Mr. Miles distributed a  <A HREF="03-11-96.attatch6.html">chart </A> of the TSSDS entity classes and the FGDC Subcommittee standardizing in that area.  He proposed that the Facilities Working Group select some entities or themes that are not currently be addressed by the FGDC to standardize on.  The Group stated that they might be interested in initially standardizing on the information in the TSSDS entities of Utilities, Buildings, Improvements, Communications, and Environmental Hazards.  In the future, they would consider the other unaddressed areas.  Mr. Smith explained the structure and content of the TSSDS and explained that this could be reviewed on the CD that was mailed to the Group last September or they could download the TSSDS from the  <A HREF="http://mr2.wes.army.mil">Tri-Service Center Server </A>.
	 <LI>ACTION: Review the TSSDS information in Utilities, Buildings, Improvements, Communications, and Environmental Hazards.  Be prepared to propose any changes required to meet your agency needs at the next meeting.  Be prepared to propose a standard to the FGDC (GROUP).  
 </UL>

7) Misc: 
 <UL>
	 <LI>Mr. McHugh asked that someone from the Tri-Service CADD/GIS Technology Center make a presentation on the TSSDS at the New York Metropolitan Transit Authority CADD/GIS User Group meeting (April 23).   Mr. Miles said that a letter of invitation is not required unless it is useful for the requestor's internal purposes.  In this case, send a letter to Mr. Miles requesting a presentation on the Facilities Working Group topic of interest to you.

	 <LI>The American Planning Association (APA) conference is 13-17 April in Kissimmee, FL and the first APA Federal Planning Division (FPD) conference will be held 17-19 April in Kissimmee.  The Facilities Working Group Chair will give a presentation on the FGDC, Facilities Working Group, and EO 12906 at the FPD conference.
 </UL>

8)  Next Meeting: The next two meetings will be 8 April and 13 May from 1-4 in the Pulaski Building, 20 Massachusetts Avenue, NW, Washington, DC. 

 </BODY>
 </HTML>
</DOC>
