 <HTML>
 <HEAD>
 <TITLE>Minutes from 31 October, 1995  </TITLE>

 <H1>MINUTES: </H1> <P>
 </HEAD>

 <BODY>
      Enclosed is a summary report from the 31 October meeting of the Federal 
Geographic Data Committee (FGDC) Facilities Working Group.  We are not 
including all the handouts distributed at the meeting, as they are voluminous.  
If you are interested in copies of these we will mail them to you upon request 
or provide them to you at the next meeting.  The next meeting will be 
 <A HREF="../next_meeting.html">21 December from 1-4 </A>, Room 8222D of the 
Pulaski Building.  This is the Headquarters for the U.S. Army Corps of 
Engineers and is located 2 blocks west of Union Station.  The main agenda item 
is to precisely define the term facility in preparation for the group's 
standards development activities. There may also be some presentations on 
STEP and SDTS/CADD Profile development. <P>

      If you have any questions about the Facilities Working Group please 
contact me at COMM 202-761-8885, FAX 202-761-4002, or Internet 
 <a href = "mailto:moody.miles@inet.hq.usace.army.mil">moody.miles@inet.hq.usace.army.mil </a>.  You may also contact the alternate chair, 
Ms Penny Capps at COMM 202-761-8893, FAX 202-761-4002, or Internet 
 <a href = "mailto:penny.capps@inet.hq.usace.army.mil">penny.capps@inet.hq.usace.army.mil </a>.

       Sincerely, <P>



       Moody K. Miles, III,  P.E., L.S. <BR>
       Chair, Facilities Working Group <P>
 <HR>

Summary Report <P> <P>


 <H3>
Federal Geographic Data Committee (FGDC) <BR>
 Facilities Working Group Meeting  <BR>
31 October 1995  <P>

Headquarters, U.S. Army Corps of Engineers (USACE) <BR>
 Pulaski Building, Washington, DC <P>
 </H4>

1)  Persons Attending:   <A HREF="./minutes_10-31-95.attatch1.html">Attendance roster </A> <P>

* See attached  <A HREF="./minutes_10-31-95.attatch2.html">agenda </A>  <P>

2)  Update on FGDC Activities - Penny Capps (USACE): <UL> 
  <LI>New Natural Resources Working Group to meet on 15 Nov from 9-3.  Call Gale 
TeSelle (202-720- 5421) for details. <BR>
  <LI>Our meetings are being announced in the Federal Register (a copy of the 
announcement was provided at the meeting). <BR>
  <LI>Minutes will soon be available on the USACE Clearinghouse node 
(http://corps_geo1.usace.army.mil)  and linked to FGDC homepage.
 </UL>

3)  FGDC Subcommittee and Working Group Status Summary Report -  <UL>
	 <LI>Denise Perreca/Richard Hogan (Standards Working Group):
Several contractors met with all the subcommittees and working groups to 
discuss their standards development issues and progress, scope of the group, 
etc.  Mr. Peter Croswell (PlanGraphics) and Ms Denise Perreca (FGDC) attended 
the 21 Sep Facilities Working Group meeting for this purpose.   Ms Perreca 
distributed a draft of the summary report prepared by the contractors.  The 
Standards Working Group and contractors will brief this FGDC Standards Summary 
Report to all FGDC members on 17 Nov from 9-12 at the USGS auditorium. An RSVP 
is requested.  Comments will be accepted until 7 December and the final paper 
is due by the end of 1995. 
 <UL> <LI> ACTION: Facilities Working Group members to review the paper, especially the 
sections on the Facilities Working Group, and provide comments to the Standards 
Working Group by 7 December 1995.
 </UL>
 <LI>Ms Perreca also distributed the latest version of the FGDC Standards 
Reference Model.  This describes the types of standards that the FGDC is 
developing and the process for approval of those standards.
  <UL> <LI>ACTION: Facilities Working Group members to provide comments to Ms Perreca by 17 November.
 </UL>
 <LI>Mr. Hogan (USGS) mentioned that we should get more involved with the 
International Standards Organization (ISO) especially STEP. 
 <UL> <LI> ACTION:  Mr. Hogan to provide Facilities Working Group Chair with STEP POC info and Chair to arrange a briefing on this topic at a Facilities Working Group meeting. 
 </UL> <br>
 </UL>
4) Unique Facilities Identification Special Interest Group (David Hammond, USCG):
Mr. Hammond summarized the information that this group gathered.  The Facilities Working Group members decided to propose a Facilities ID Standard to the FGDC.  Here are some of the remarks that led to that decision, as well as issues that must be resolved and reflected in a proposal:
 <UL> 
  <LI> Facility must be defined more precisely before we pursue a standard.  
There was concern about defining a facility to include events such as a toxic 
spill or mobile sorts of facilities (apparently EPA wants to do this but was 
not there to explain or confirm this).  Mr. Dan McHugh (NY City Transit 
Authority) recommended that we consider the individual entities that are 
facilities as well those things that are networked to comprise a facility.  
The group will spend most of the 21 December meeting resolving this and early 
discussions on the definition are 
 <A HREF="./minutes_10-31-95.attatch3.html">attached </A>.
  <LI> There are existing codes (GSA, DoD, EPA) what are not universal and have 
intelligence imbedded in them.  The Facilities Working Group does not think 
that an intelligent scheme is the way to go (especially after meeting with 
Bellcore on their implementation) but does not want to require agencies to redo 
existing codes.  This is an important criteria to consider in developing a 
facilities standard and could be as simple (?) as adding a new, non-intelligent 
code to existing intelligent codes.
  <LI> Major Costigan (Army) spoke to the modeling community within the Defense 
Environmental Corporate Information Management (DECIM) group and they 
recommended a non-intelligent schema.   Mr. Harold Smith (Tri-Service Center) 
recommended that the DoD reps talk to the DECIM about this standard in the 
hopes of acquiring resources from them to get the standard developed. 
  <LI> There were pros and cons with regard to a central register for these
 codes. The closer the ID register is to the owner the more likely it is that 
the information will be current (con).  A central register provides more 
consistency and less of a burden to more agencies (pro).  Mr. Hogan said the 
banking industry has figured out how to handle this distributed ID problem but 
it might not be the solution for the geospatial data community.
  <LI> Mr. Hogan was disappointed to hear Mr. Wiant (Army) say that the Army has 
little funds to support this sort of effort because during a recent trip to 
Korea, he learned that they are embarking on a huge digitization effort of the 
country and are looking to coordinate with the U.S. Army.  This could be an 
opportunity for the Army to take a lead in this type of work.  Ms Capps 
remarked that the Army Corps sees the benefit in such a standard and might 
be able to allocate some funds towards its development.
  <LI> Major Costigan suggested using latitudes and longitudes as ID codes.  
Members of the group explained that this would not be effective because there 
are multiple features at the same lat/long, there are multiple features at 
different elevations of the same lat/long, and some facilities are mobile.
  <LI> Ms Capps remarked that there is some sort of building ID development 
on-going between the National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) and 
the U.S. Army Construction Engineering Research Laboratories (CERL).  She and 
Mr. Hammond have not been able to reach POCs.
  <LI> ACTION: Chair to distribute a draft proposal for a FGDC Facilities ID 
Standard to the Facilities Working Group members.  Members  to provide 
additional information (agency need for such a standard, resources to develop 
standard, etc.) and comments on this proposal.  Chair and Mr. Hammond 
to resolve comments and prepare a draft for presentation in early 1996.  
  <LI> ACTION: Chair to distribute early discussions on definition of facility 
so that members can prepare for the 21 December discussions.
  <LI> ACTION:   Chair and Mr. Hammond to contact NIST and CERL about their 
building ID standard development efforts.
 </UL>
5) Unique Feature IDs for the National Geospatial Data Framework 
(Mike Domaratz, FGDC): 
Mr. Domaratz was invited to brief the group about Framework efforts in case 
there might be some commonality between the Framework and Facility Working 
Group approaches to unique feature id schemas.  The FGDC is funding Framework 
pilots and recently held a meeting of the pilot project managers in Charleston, 
SC.  The group: <UL> 
  <LI>Talked about the possible need for different ID schemes for raster and 
vector data
  <LI>Said that Linear Referencing Systems (LRS) might be a suitable ID scheme 
for transportation data but there are multiple LRS even at the state level
  <LI>Thought that the USGS/EPA River Reach codes seem appropriate but there 
will need to be a crosswalk between state codes and the River Reach codes
  <LI>Questioned feature ID codes that could illustrate nested (one feature 
inside of another feature) features
  <LI>Said that the FIPS 55 codes for boundaries were fine. 
 </UL>  

6)  Tri-Service Spatial Data Standards (Capps/Smith):
Mr. Smith gave a quick summary of the Tri-Service Spatial Data Standards (TSSDS).
  The group decided that they would propose the TSSDS as an FGDC standard but 
needed to see it in a different form before they could agree to anything more 
definite, i.e. propose the entire TSSDS or just a portion of it as an FGDC 
standard.  The group recommended that Messrs Smith and Backe reformat the 
TSSDS into the pieces that each FGDC subcommittee or working group would need 
to review, remove agency policies, etc. and then present it to the Facilities 
Working Group for more consideration.   Here are some of the discussions that 
led to this, issues to be resolved or considered, etc.: <UL>
  <LI> There were a lot of remarks on physical model vs. logical model.  The 
TSSDS provides both and can be implemented in several commercial platforms as 
well as GRASS.  This can be an advantage to some users and will be provided as 
a bonusor guide when proposed as an FGDC standard.  It is important for the 
FGDC to not appear to be promoting a particular vendor product but helpful to 
provide available tools to the users.  Mr. Smith would like to keep the TSSDS 
in digital form and said that he could provide the user with buttons on the 
screens to view only those sections of the TSSDS that are being proposed as an 
FGDC standard and still give access to other possible useful information.  
Ms Perreca said that the FGDC Standards Working Group has not set a standard 
for proposing or distributing an FGDC standard.
  <LI> Mr. Racht (USACE) wondered who is going to pay for moving this standard 
through the FGDC process and won't there be a big burden to the DoD facilities 
community every time the TSSDS is modified to be compatible with an emerging 
FGDC standard?  Ms Capps explained that there are some funds in the Tri-Service 
Center budget to specifically cover coordination with the FGDC and that at an 
earlier meeting Mr. Riegelmann (Tri-Service Center) explained that changes to 
the TSSDS would result in a backwardly compatible version.  Mr. Wiant said that 
being able to share data with the local communities warrants moving the TSSDS 
through the FGDC process.  He said this would help us work with our Federal 
Brothers and State Siblings per the Federal Facilities Compliance Act.
  <LI> Mr. Backe explained that because of its large scale/detailed focus, 
the TSSDS could really help bring the FGDC down to the local level and give 
the locals a useful data standard.
  <LI> Ms Capps explained that because of the commitment to coordinate with the 
FGDC, the Center would have to work with subcommittees on the TSSDS regardless 
of the decision of the Facilities Working Group to propose it as a standard.
  <LI> Ms Perreca said that the TSSDS should be briefed as either a standard 
that must incorporate existing/emerging FGDC standards or as something for 
groups to consider adopting if they currently do not have a standard.
  <LI> Mr. Smith explained that the TSSDS uses common tables that are shared and 
therefore has no overlap.  This is something that the FGDC should shoot for.
  <LI> Mr. Hogan relayed the interest at the ANSI X3L1 level to promote the 
TSSDS as a joint Canada/U.S. feature standard.  Mr. Hogan expressed his belief 
that the TSSDS is mature enough to do this.  He also explained that there was 
confusion about the TSSDS, i.e. was it already an FGDC standard because it 
looked so official?  Ms. Capps explained that it was distributed on CD for the 
DoD facilities community to use and therefore was not marked as a Draft.  
It was also distributed outside of this community for comment and/or use.  It 
was not intended to look like an FGDC blessed standard and the accompanying 
cover letter explained this.
  <LI>ACTION:  Messrs Smith and Backe to reformat the TSSDS and present to the 
Facilities Working Group as soon as possible.
 </UL>

7)  Update Work Plan and Charter and write 1995 Accomplishments (Capps):
The FGDC would like updates to group charters and descriptions of 
accomplishments by 17 November.  The group can not do this until they agree 
on a definition of facility at the 21 December meeting. <UL>
  <LI>ACTION: The Chair will fax group members a draft list of accomplishments 
for review.
 </UL>

8) Misc.: GIS/LIS 95 is 13-16 November in Nashville, TN.  There will not be an 
FGDC Coordination Group meeting there but there will be some FGDC members on 
panel discussions and a DoD Data Standards panel discussion (including the 
TSSDS). <P>


9) Next Meeting: The  <A HREF="../next_meeting.html">next meeting </A> will be 
21 December from 1-4 in room 8222D of the Pulaski Building, 20 Massachusetts 
Avenue, NW, Washington, DC.
 <HR>
