<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//W3O/DTD HTML//EN">

<html>
<head>
<title>The Drug Development Cycle</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body background="images/backgrnd.gif">
<h2 align="center"><u><MAP NAME="FrontPageMap"><AREA SHAPE="RECT" COORDS="2, 2, 103, 37" HREF="index.htm"></MAP><a href="/corningb/_vti_map/ddc.htm.map"><img
align="bottom" src="images/home.gif" width="104" alt="Home Page"
ismap usemap="#FrontPageMap" height="38" border="0"></a></u></h2>
<h2 align="center"><img src="IMAGES/LOGO.GIF" align="bottom"
width="363" height="31"></h2>
<h1 align="center"><u>The Drug Development Cycle</u></h1>
<h2><u>Introduction</u></h2>
<p>Drugs are identified as potentially useful in the treatment of
disease, via intensive research within pharmaceutical companies
and academia. Before a drug can be marketed, it must be
thoroughly tested to ensure that it is both safe and that it is
effective against targeted diseases or conditions.This process is
often referred to as the drug development cycle and is made up of
a number of phases.</p>
<h2><a href="hazel.htm">Preclinical</a></h2>
<p>Prior to the administration of drugs to humans, preclinical
studies are conducted using both animal (in vivo) and non-animal
tests (in vitro). In vitro studies include tests on bacteria and
human cells. In-vivo studies are used as predictors of the safety
of the product in people. These tests give information about the
way the drug works and how safe it is. <a href="hazel.htm">Corning
Hazleton</a> is the World&#146;s leading company involved in
preclinical drug safety assessments.</p>
<h2><a href="phasei.htm">Phase I</a></h2>
<p>Once the preclinical data for a drug have been assessed and
the drug has been deemed to be safe, it enters the clinical
phase. This is where the drug is tested in humans. The first
studies in man are usually performed in healthy volunteers and
are termed Phase I studies. Volunteers are paid for their
participation in these studies. They are designed to give a
preliminary evaluation of the drug&#146;s safety and of how the
drug is treated by the body (pharmacokinetics). Most Phase I
studies are conducted in specialised Phase I units, where
experienced medical personnel are available to ensure the safety
of the volunteers. Such a unit is the<a href="phasei.htm">
Corning Besselaar Clinical Research Unit</a> in Leeds, UK, which
is regarded as Europe&#146;s leading <a href="phasei.htm">Phase I</a>
unit. </p>
<h2><a href="phaseii.htm">Phase II</a></h2>
<p>If the drug causes no adverse effects in the Phase I studies
and has the required pharmacokinetic properties, it can progress
to Phase II studies. At this stage the drug is tested in patients
with the intended disease or condition for the first time. These
studies are performed in a small number of patients (typically 10
to 20) and explore the safety and effectiveness of the drug
(efficacy), often against placebo (non-drug) controls. At this
stage the effective therapeutic dose to be used in further trials
will be explored.<a href="phaseii.htm"> Corning Besselaar Phase
II Europe</a> is a dedicated group set up for the conduct of
these specialised clinical trials.</p>
<h2><a href="phaseiii.htm">Phase III</a></h2>
<p>Phase III trials are large scale studies to study the efficacy
and safety of the new drug, prior to the drug being registered
with the regulatory authorities. These studies are often
long-term and involve a sufficiently high number of patients to
be able to prove the efficacy of the drug. The safety profile of
the drug during these studies is examined closely to determine
the risk to benefit ratio of the drug. Frequently the new drug is
compared to other drugs which are already marketed for the
drug&#146;s intended disease or condition. Corning Besselaar is
the World&#146;s leading clinical contract research organisation.
One of the critical components of phase III is the collection of
data. This function is provided by our dedicated <a
href="edmc.htm">European Data Management Centre (EDMC)</a> which
processes clinical trial data and produces a clinical trial
report for submission to the regulatory authorities.</p>
<h2><a href="health.htm">Health Economics</a></h2>
<p>The study of economic factors in clinical trials <a
href="health.htm">(pharmacoeconomics)</a> is becoming more
prevalent. The pressures to lower drug prices means that a drug
has to be proved not only effective and safe but also that it is
cost-effective. Corning Pharmaceutical Services has recently
acquired Health Technology Associates (HTA), forming Corning HTA,
who are specialists in this field.</p>
<h2><a href="pact.htm">Phase IV</a></h2>
<p><a href="pact.htm">Phase IV</a> studies are typically
performed after the regulatory authority grants marketing
approval for the drug. They are used to continue to build the
database on the safety of the drug which may reveal rare
side-effects or interactions or to support the further use of the
drug for it&#146;s indication. <a href="pact.htm">Corning PACT</a>
perform these studies in the US whilst <a href="intro.htm">Corning
Besselaar</a> perform these studies in the UK.</p>
<h2><u>Other Corning Pharmaceutical Services organisations that
support the Drug Development Cycle.</u></h2>
<h3>Global centralised clinical laboratory services</h3>
<p><a href="http://www.bio.com/scicor.html">Corning SciCor</a>
lab services are dedicated exclusively to pharmaceutical studies.
They currently service sites in over 47 countries. They offer
combinable data worldwide, comprehensive specimen management,
consistent methodology and multilingual customer support</p>
<h3>Full service bioprocessing</h3>
<p><a href="http://www.bio.com/bio.html">Corning Bio</a> offers
outsourced cGMP manufacturing services to the biopharmaceutical
community. It's state-of-the-art 109,000 square foot
bioprocessing facility in Research Triangle Park, North Carolina,
USA will manufacture recombitant peptide and protein products to
cGMP standards for pre-clinical and clinical trials, as well as
for phase III and commercial production.</p>
<h3>Pharmaceutical packaging</h3>
<p><a href="http://www.bio.com/natpack.html">Corning National
Packaging</a> offers full-service Contract Packaging. It is the
industry leader in the development, design and production of
packaging for clinical trials. Corning National Packaging offers
a complete service, from package development and design, to
clinical supplies management.</p>
<h3>Non-clinical development</h3>
<p><a href="phasei.htm">Corning Hazleton</a> offers safety
assessment and drug disposition facilities and has over 50 years
experience in toxicology testing, chemistry services, product
releasing testing. Corning Hazleton offers compound appraisal and
selection and comprehensive toxicology facilities.</p>
<hr>
