<head>
<title>Good Clinical Practice. (GCP)</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body background="images/backgrnd.gif">
<p align="center"><MAP NAME="FrontPageMap"><AREA SHAPE="RECT" COORDS="2, 2, 103, 37" HREF="index.htm"><AREA COORDS="0,0,10000,10000" HREF="index.htm"></MAP><a href="/corningb/_vti_map/gcp.htm.map"><img
align="bottom" src="images/home.gif" width="104" alt="Home Page"
ismap usemap="#FrontPageMap" height="38" border="0"></a></p>
<h1><u>Good Clinical Practice (GCP)</u></h1>
<p>Good Clinical Practice (GCP) is a standard for the design,
conduct, performance, monitoring, auditing, recording, analyses
and reporting of <a href="ddc.htm">clinical trials</a>. It
provides the assurance that the data and reported results are
credible and accurate and that the rights, integrity and
confidentiality of trial subjects are protected. </p>
<p>GCP standards were developed and enforced as recommendations
in the European Community as of July, 1991. The driving force
behind them were disclosures of fraud, quality of clinical
studies varied greatly between investigators and countries and
clinical studies have failed to be pivotal for purely technical
reasons. The results of these problems caused the need to repeat
studies, increased cost of Research and Development and increased
time to market. </p>
<p>The development GCP has a chequered history starting in 1963
with IND regulations, 1964 Declaration of Helsinki, 1976 German
Drug Law, 1978 Spanish Decree, 1980 Nordic Guidelines on Clinical
Trials of Drugs, 1984 Greek Law, 1987 French, German Guidelines,
1988 UK Guideline, 1989 Nordic Guideline, 1991 EC GCP Note for
Guidance and 1993 EC Directive 91/507 on GCP. </p>
<p>The EC GCP for Trial on Medicinal Products is a document with
58 articles in 5 chapters and an annex. It covers: a Glossary,
Protection of Trial Subjects and Consultation of Ethics
Committees, Responsibilities, Data Handling, Statistics and
Quality Assurance. </p>
<p>All Corning Besselaar Europe employees must attend GCP
training seminars. This enables them to gain knowledge of the
fundamentals of GCP in order to follow it in their working
practice. Each employee is also provided with a concise booklet
entitled 'European GCP Note for Guidance' on starting with the
company. </p>
<hr>
<p align="center"><MAP NAME="FrontPageMap1"><AREA SHAPE="RECT" COORDS="366, 5, 456, 107" HREF="library.htm"><AREA SHAPE="RECT" COORDS="278, 7, 363, 103" HREF="cps.htm"><AREA SHAPE="RECT" COORDS="187, 7, 272, 103" HREF="caropps.htm"><AREA SHAPE="RECT" COORDS="97, 7, 182, 103" HREF="contact.htm"><AREA SHAPE="RECT" COORDS="6, 7, 92, 103" HREF="index.htm"><AREA COORDS="0,0,10000,10000" HREF="index.htm"></MAP><a href="/corningb/_vti_map/gcp.htm.1.map"><img
