<html>
<head>
<title>Process Validation:Why Validate</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body background="images/backgrnd.gif">
<h4 align="center"><MAP NAME="FrontPageMap"><AREA SHAPE="RECT" COORDS="0, 0, 102, 37" HREF="INDEX.HTM"></MAP><a href="/corningb/_vti_map/procval2.htm.map"><img
align="bottom" src="IMAGES/home.gif" width="104" ismap
usemap="#FrontPageMap" height="38" border="0"></a></h4>
<h4 align="center"><img src="images/cps2.gif" align="bottom"
width="306" height="45"></h4>
<h4>A Guide to Process Validation for Pharmaceuticals Produced in
Mammalian Cell Culture </h4>
<h1 align="left"><u>Why Validate the Purification Process </u>? </h1>
<p align="left">The regulations for licensing of
biopharmaceuticals recommend that safety tests be carried out at
various stages of the manufacturing process. The main emphases of
this testing are on the source material, the bulk product and the
purification process. By thorough testing of the cell banks and
bulk product it is possible to demonstrate that no detectable
virus is present. However, for a number of reasons outlined
below, it is also necessary to validate the process for viral
clearance. </p>
<ul>
    <li>The possibility exists that a new virus will arise and
        that it is not detected in the cell bank or source
        material testing. An example of this was the transmission
        of AIDS by contaminated Factor VIII. This occurred when
        HIV first arose in the population and was not detectable
        by the techniques then employed. By demonstrating that
        the process can clear a wide range of viruses with
        different stabilities and physicochemical properties, a
        manufacturer can impart confidence that any novel virus
        will be cleared from the product. </li>
    <li>Process validation provides some security in case of a
        failure in another part of the system. If a latent virus
        is present in the cell banks but has remained undetected,
        or if a new virus is introduced due to a failure of GMP,
        then the knowledge that the process is capable of
        removing high titres of virus imparts a degree of
        confidence to the safety of the product. </li>
    <li>Some cell lines with important medical potential are
        endogenously infected with virus. Murine hybridoma cell
        banks contain both A- and C-type particles. The A-type
        form intracisternaly where they remain sequestered and do
        not develop further. C-type particles are usually present
        in smaller numbers than A-type particles, but some
        C-types are infectious and are classified according to
        the host range they exhibit i.e ecotropic, xenotropic,
        polytropic or amphotropic. Another example of a cell line
        which is endogenously infected with retrovirus-like
        particles is CHO. All CHO cell lines contain both A- and
        C-type particles but there is no evidence that these are
        infectious. Hence the CHO cell line differs from a murine
        hybridoma in that it has not been shown to produce
        retroviruses capable of horizontal infection. Since it is
        not possible to access a source of retrovirus-free CHO
        cell lines or to have retrovirus free murine hybridomas,
        the only way to demonstrate the safety of a product from
        hybridoma or CHO cells is to show that the purification
        process will clear any potential virus present in the
        starting materials. </li>
    <li>During the cell line characterisation, aliquots are taken
        and assayed for the presence of a range of possible
        contaminants. Even if the results of these tests are
        negative, there remains the possibility that the cell
        bank contains virus not detected due to the statistical
        limitations of sampling. Thus testing of the cell banks
        can never demonstrate that they are absolutely free of
        contamination. </li>
</ul>
<p align="left">It follows therefore, that to give a high level
of confidence in the safety of the final product it is also
necessary to demonstrate that any undetected viral contamination
will be cleared during purification of the product. </p>
<p align="left">The process validation is an integral part of the
testing strategy and should be considered in relation to the cell
line characterisation. As discussed below, the planning of the
validation programme, and the levels of clearance required, will
depend partly on the results of the virus detection assays
carried out on the Master cell bank, bulk product and maximum end
of production cells. </p>
<p align="center">&#160;</p>
<table width="100%">
    <tr>
        <td width="50%"> 
        <p align="right"><img src="IMAGES/th_up.gif"
        align="bottom" width="25" height="19"> <a
        href="procindx.htm">Return to Contents</a> </p>
        </td>
        <td width="50%"> 
        <p align="left"><img src="IMAGES/r_hand.gif"
        align="bottom" width="33" height="14"> <a
        href="procval3.htm">Next page</a></p>
        </td>
    </tr>
</table>
<hr>
<p align="center"><MAP NAME="FrontPageMap1"><AREA SHAPE="RECT" COORDS="95, 0, 184, 109" HREF="CONTACT.HTM"><AREA SHAPE="RECT" COORDS="185, 1, 274, 109" HREF="CAROPPS.HTM"><AREA SHAPE="RECT" COORDS="275, 1, 366, 109" HREF="CPS.HTM"><AREA SHAPE="RECT" COORDS="364, 1, 459, 109" HREF="library.htm"><AREA SHAPE="RECT" COORDS="1, 1, 95, 109" HREF="INDEX.HTM"></MAP><a href="/corningb/_vti_map/procval2.htm.1.map"><img
align="bottom" src="IMAGES/BUTTONS.GIF" width="460" ismap
usemap="#FrontPageMap1" height="110" border="0"></a></p>
