</DOCHDR>
<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//W3O/DTD HTML//EN">

<html>
<head>
<title>Process Validation:Viruses Used</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body background="images/backgrnd.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
link="#000080">
<h4 align="center"><MAP NAME="FrontPageMap"><AREA SHAPE="RECT" COORDS="2, 2, 103, 37" HREF="INDEX.HTM"></MAP><a href="/corningb/_vti_map/procval3.htm.map"><img
align="bottom" src="IMAGES/home.gif" width="104" ismap
usemap="#FrontPageMap" height="38" border="0"></a></h4>
<h4 align="center"><img src="IMAGES/cps2.gif" align="bottom"
width="306" height="45"></h4>
<h4>A Guide to Process Validation for Pharmaceuticals Produced in
Mammalian Cell Culture </h4>
<h1><u>Viruses to be used in the Validation </u></h1>
<h2>Considerations regarding the choice of virus </h2>
<p>From the discussion above, it follows that the purification
process should be validated for the clearance of a range of
viruses. This is done by spiking chosen stages of a scaled down
version of the purification process with a known high titre of
challenge virus. The titre of virus is then re-assayed after each
treatment, and the reductions caused by each purification stage
are used to determine an overall clearance factor for the
process.The choice of virus used in the validation depends on a
variety of factors. </p>
<h4>Cell line used in production </h4>
<p>The number and type of virus to be used in the testing of a
hybridoma cell line will depend on the origin of the cell line
i.e. mouse, rat or human. A minimum of three viruses is required
in the validation but more may be necessary. Where a virus is
known to be present in the cell line, one should demonstrate that
the process can clear high enough titres of that virus, or of a
similar model virus, to give confidence that no virus will remain
in the final product. Thus a process validation for a murine
hybridoma product should include a murine retrovirus.A well
characterised hamster cell line, such as CHO, which has been
shown to be free from adventitious agents poses a relatively low
risk. On this basis we believe a strong case can be made for
validating the purification process with only three viruses.In
contrast a product purified from human blood may be considered as
relatively high risk, and it may be necessary to include four or
more viruses in the validation.Where possible the viruses should
be relevant ie. viruses which are able and likely to infect the
production cell. However, where a cell line does not exhibit a
wide host-range (CHO cells fit into this category) or where it is
not possible to assay for the virus of principle concern (eg
there is no in vitro culture assay for hepatitis B virus) certain
model viruses are proposed. </p>
<h4>Range of viruses to be included </h4>
<p>The process should also be validated against a range of virus
types with different physicochemical properties and stabilities.
Points to consider in selecting these viruses include the type of
nucleic acid present in the genome and whether they possess a
lipid envelope. The range of viruses used should include at least
one that is known to be difficult to inactivate. Poliovirus, for
example, is suitable in this regard since it is small and
non-enveloped. Hepatitis A is now widely used at <a
href="HAZEL.HTM">Corning Hazleton</a> as this is significantly
more resistant to heat treatment than poliovirus and a
quantitative plaque assay has been developed. </p>
<h4>Availability of high titre stocks in serum-free medium </h4>
<p>The maximum possible clearance which can be demonstrated for a
particular purification step depends on the starting titre of the
virus stock. Hence it is advantageous to start with virus stocks
which are as high titre as possible. The titres of some of the
stocks available at Corning Hazleton are shown in Appendix 1. </p>
<h4>Plaque assays vs TCID50 </h4>
<p>Plaque assays allow for a more accurate determination of
residual titre than a TCID50 assay. Therefore to obtain viral
clearance factors with high degrees of statistical significance
it is preferable to use the plaque assay. However, there are some
viruses which cannot be titred by plaque assay, including
maedi-visna virus and porcine parvovirus (PPV), and for these
Corning Hazleton uses a TCID50 assay. </p>
<h2>Example of the choice of virus </h2>
<p>To illustrate these points the viruses we recommend for a
either a murine hybridoma or for a CHO-derived product are
discussed below. </p>
<h4>Hybridoma process validation </h4>
<p>We are assuming that no contaminants have been detected in the
cell banks other than A-type and C-type retroviruses, and the
purification methods are varied and stringent. However the
requirements will depend on the type of hybridoma e.g
murine-murine, human-murine or human-human. A minimum of 3
viruses should be used in the process validation and appropriate
viruses are described below.All hybridomas should be tested for
clearance of retroviruses. For murine hybridomas the clearance of
murine leukaemia virus (MuLV) should be demonstrated as this
virus is present in murine lymphoid cells. This virus is also
useful in the validation of murine-human hybridomas.Herpesviruses
may occur in murine lymphoid cells and so should be included in
the validation process. Where human cells are used it is also
necessary to demonstrate clearance of herpesviruses and it is of
particular importance to demonstrate clearance of herpesvirus if
EBV has been used in producing the hybridoma. Herpesviruses are
double stranded DNA enveloped viruses and HSV-1 and infectious
bovine rhinotracheitis virus (IBRV) are suitable models.A
picornavirus such as polio should also be used. This is a small,
non-enveloped RNA virus which is difficult to kill and so can
demonstrate the stringency of the process.In addition, it is
necessary to demonstrate clearance of the retrovirus subgroup,
lentivirus when human cells are used. Maedi-visna virus is an
appropriate model virus for this purpose.Other viruses should be
included as required depending on the history of the cells used
to make the hybridoma. </p>
<h4>CHO cell process validation </h4>
<p>We are assuming that no contaminants have been detected in the
cell banks other than A-type and C-type retroviruses, and the
purification methods are varied and stringent. Hence it is
possible to use only three viruses.The choice of Parainfluenza
type 3 (PI3) virus meets the requirement for a relevant virus as
it is infectious for CHO cells. It is medium sized, enveloped and
relatively labile.The choice of a retrovirus is almost mandatory
in these circumstances since apparently all CHO lines possess
non-infectious A type retroviruses. We include a murine
xenotropic retrovirus as a model retrovirus to fulfil this
condition.Poliovirus is a good model virus because it is
relatively stable to inactivation and is one of the smallest
viruses.If the clearance is predicted to be due to processes
which inactivate by interaction with nucleic acid, it may be
sensible to also include a DNA virus. Suitable candidates would
be either SV40 virus (which is, like poliovirus, a relatively
resistant virus) or herpes simplex (which is enveloped).This
range includes enveloped and non-enveloped viruses and those with
DNA and RNA genomes. All of these viruses are available at
Corning Hazleton at high titre. Other viruses available at
Corning Hazleton are shown in Appendix 1. </p>
<p align="center">&#160;</p>
<table width="100%">
    <tr>
        <td width="50%"> 
        <p align="right"><img src="IMAGES/th_up.gif"
        align="bottom" width="25" height="19"> <a
        href="libcon.htm">Return to Contents</a> </p>
        </td>
        <td width="50%"> 
        <p align="left"><img src="IMAGES/r_hand.gif"
        align="bottom" width="33" height="14"> <a
        href="procval4.htm">Next page</a></p>
        </td>
    </tr>
</table>
