<html>
<head>
<title>Process Validation:Initial Studies</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body background="images/backgrnd.gif">
<h4 align="center"><img src="IMAGES/home.gif" align="bottom"
width="104" height="38"></h4>
<h4 align="center"><img src="images/cps2.gif" align="bottom"
width="306" height="45"></h4>
<h4>A Guide to Process Validation for Pharmaceuticals Produced in
Mammalian Cell Culture </h4>
<h1>Initial Studies </h1>
<h2>Introduction </h2>
<p>There are various factors which need to be fully considered
before validation, and we are happy to advise clients on all
aspects of the experimentation. In our experience much time and
effort can be saved by detailed discussions between ourselves and
the client, and we encourage clients to come to us as early as
possible to accomplish this. </p>
<h2>The selection of the stages of the process to be validated </h2>
<p>Where two individual stages remove or inactivate virus by
different chemical or physical means, the reduction of viral
titre for each stage may be multiplied together to arrive at a
total clearance factor for the two stages. Where the stages
operate by similar methods the clearances must be added, because
of the possibility that a fraction of virus remaining after the
first stage will be resistant to the second stage. Hence it is
recommended that, where possible, the stages selected for
validation should clear virus by different modes of action, in
order to maximise the demonstrable clearance. Corning Hazleton
can advise on the best approach when choosing the stages to
validate. </p>
<h2>Process scale-down </h2>
<p>The US and European regulations require that the data provided
on validity of scale down should be satisfactory, and it will be
necessary to compare the behaviour of the scaled down and full
scale processes.Technical problems may arise where the degree of
scale down is too extensive, since the use of very small volumes
leads to a decrease in the accuracy of the virological detection
methods. It is also important to ensure the addition of virus
does not substantially dilute, or alter in other ways, the
composition of the load buffer. For this reason, the volume of
virus suspension added should not normally exceed 10% v/v of the
starting solution. The actual volumes used will depend on the
process, but typically we recommend aiming to work with solutions
of about 10ml, and spiking with 0.5ml of virus. High titre,
serum-free virus is of great value in this respect.It should also
be noted that the scale down ratio does not need to be the same
for all parts of a process. Thus an early stage which deals with
very large volumes may need to be scaled down more than a later
stage which deals with correspondingly smaller volumes. In all
cases however, adequate data must be provided to show there is
good correlation between the activity of the product or other
markers in the full-scale process and in the scale down. </p>
<h2>Cytotoxicity and viral interference assay </h2>
<p>It is most important to determine the toxicity of the
solutions used in the process before starting the validation.
This is done by adding serial dilutions of the test solutions to
the indicator cell monolayers. The monolayers are then cultured,
and the maximum concentration of the test solution which does not
cause toxic effect is noted.A concentration of test solution
which is non-cytotoxic may still interfere with viral infectivity
assay. Viral interference may take place because test solutions
alter cell surface receptors, or because they change the
electrostatic charges on the surface of cell and virus. To
investigate this, indicator monolayers are prepared in serial
dilutions of the test solution. They are then inoculated with a
known number of plaque forming units of selected virus. The
numbers of plaques which are formed at different concentrations
of the test solution are then compared, and the maximum
concentration of test solution which does not cause cytotoxicity
or viral interference is then selected for use in the validation.
An example is shown in Appendix 2. Further problems are caused if
the product itself interferes with the assay such as in the case
of certain cytokines. In these circumstances it may be acceptable
to carry out the validation in the absence of the product whilst
ensuring the overall protein concentration is maintained. </p>
<p align="center">&#160;</p>
<table width="100%">
    <tr>
        <td width="50%"> 
        <p align="right"><img src="IMAGES/th_up.gif"
        align="bottom" width="25" height="19"> <a
        href="procindx.htm">Return to Contents</a> </p>
        </td>
        <td width="50%"> 
        <p align="left"><img src="IMAGES/r_hand.gif"
        align="bottom" width="33" height="14"> <a
        href="procval5.htm">Next page</a> </p>
        </td>
    </tr>
</table>
