<html>
<head>
<title>Process Validation:Method</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body background="images/backgrnd.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
link="#000080">
<p align="center"><img src="IMAGES/home.gif" align="bottom"
width="104" height="38"></p>
<p align="center">&#160; <img src="images/cps2.gif"
align="bottom" width="306" height="45"></p>
<h4>A Guide to Process Validation for Pharmaceuticals Produced in
Mammalian Cell Culture </h4>
<h1><u>Method of Validation</u> </h1>
<h2>Introduction </h2>
<p>During the validation each virus is added to the selected
stages, and residual titre is determined by culture assay. At <a
href="HAZEL.HTM">Corning Hazleton</a> we assay samples
immediately to give as accurate a titre as possible; a proportion
of the sample is also frozen to assay later in the event of
unforeseen difficulties. All fractions are assayed in triplicate
to obtain statistically significant results, and the validation
of each step is usually performed on two occasions for each virus
to demonstrate repeatability. </p>
<h2>Validation of purification processes </h2>
<p>For regulatory submission it is required that, where a
purification step relies on viral removal, the distribution of
the virus so removed should be investigated. This will involve
comparing the distribution of virus and product, in order to
demonstrate a margin of safety between the product peak and the
virus. Since the column eluate can be of high volume, it may be
necessary to give particular consideration to the volume of each
fraction which should be assayed. It will be particularly
important to assay a large proportion of any fraction which
contains the product, in order to demonstrate that virus and
product do not co-elute. </p>
<p>Where the virus is retained on a column, it will be required
to show that the column regeneration buffer is either virucidal
or purges the virus from the column. </p>
<h2>Kinetics of viral inactivation </h2>
<p>In order to achieve high enough viral clearance it is often
necessary to include a virus inactivation step in the process. A
number which have been successfully used by manufactures are
shown </p>
<div align="center"><center>
<table border="1" width="100%">
    <tr>
        <td align="center"> 
        <h4>Inactivation treatments </h4>
        </td>
        <td align="center"> 
        <h4>Comments </h4>
        </td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
        <td>Formaldehyde</td>
        <td>Widely used by vaccine manufacturers, this is a
        relatively stringent process</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
        <td>Solvent/detergent</td>
        <td>Causes complete inactivation of many enveloped
        viruses. Ineffective against non-enveloped viruses</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
        <td>Caprylate</td>
        <td>Effective against enveloped viruses</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
        <td>Beta propiolactone</td>
        <td>Acts against the viral genome</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
        <td>Gamma irradiation</td>
        <td>Acts against the viral genome; has been successfully
        used by animal serum manufacturers</td>
    </tr>
</table>
</center></div>
<p>Where a stage of the process inactivates virus, it is
necessary to demonstrate the kinetics of the reaction. The most
effective treatments are those which exhibit first order
kinetics, with a linear reduction in virus titre over time. Where
the reaction is not first order, there exists the possibility
that a proportion of the population is resistant to the effects
of the particular treatment, hence it may be necessary to
demonstrate greater overall clearance to impart confidence in the
system. </p>
<p>A preliminary to this will be to demonstrate that the product
is stable under the conditions of inactivation. Viruses are then
treated by the inactivation process, and samples are removed at
various time points and assayed for residual titre. An
understanding of the inactivation process is necessary to choose
which time points to assay - with some inactivation processes
virus kill is accomplished rapidly and hence early time points
will be necessary. With any process it will be advantageous to
demonstrate that all virus is inactivated before the end on the
incubation time, rather than simply assaying virus at the
beginning and end of the process. In order to assist in the
planning of validation of an inactivation step is sometimes
useful to perform an initial screening study to investigate the
effect of the process on the virus of concern (<a
href="procva10.htm">see Appendix 3</a>). </p>
<p align="center">&#160;</p>
<table width="100%">
    <tr>
        <td width="50%"> 
        <p align="right"><img src="IMAGES/th_up.gif"
        align="bottom" width="25" height="19"> <a
        href="procindx.htm">Return to Contents</a> </p>
        </td>
        <td width="50%"> 
        <p align="left"><img src="IMAGES/r_hand.gif"
        align="bottom" width="33" height="14"> <a
        href="procval6.htm">Next page</a></p>
        </td>
    </tr>
</table>
