<html>
<head>
<title>Process Validation:Results</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body background="images/backgrnd.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
link="#000080">
<h4 align="center"><MAP NAME="FrontPageMap"><AREA SHAPE="RECT" COORDS="3, 1, 103, 37" HREF="INDEX.HTM"></MAP><a href="/corningb/_vti_map/procval6.htm.map"><img
align="bottom" src="IMAGES/home.gif" width="104" ismap
usemap="#FrontPageMap" height="38" border="0"></a></h4>
<h4 align="center"><img src="images/cps2.gif" align="bottom"
width="306" height="45"></h4>
<h4>A Guide to Process Validation for Pharmaceuticals Produced in
Mammalian Cell Culture </h4>
<h1><u>Results </u></h1>
<h2>Quantification of overall viral clearance </h2>
<p>During the validation the clearance factors of individual
stages of the purification process will be determined. Depending
on whether these stages act by different mechanisms, these
factors are then added or multiplied. The final result is
expressed as a clearance factor for each virus over the whole
purification process. For all validations Corning Hazleton has a
statistics department which can assist in the planning of the
validation and in the interpretation of results. </p>
<h2>Acceptable overall clearance factors </h2>
<p>Since applications for licensing are dealt with on a
case-by-case basis, and the recommended viral clearance may vary
depending upon circumstances, it is not possible to state
categorically the clearance factor which should be achieved. This
will usually vary between the different challenge viruses. One
useful consideration is that the level of contamination of final
product should be less than or equal to one infectious unit per
one million doses. Where a known contaminant has to be removed
the initial titre can be determined and used to calculate the
necessary degree of virus removal. Thus for a murine hybridoma
product it is possible to calculate the titre of retroviruses
present in the culture supernatant by electron microscopy, and
use this to calculate the required clearance factor. Clearly this
is only a useful method where a known contaminant has to be
removed, and is not applicable to challenges using model viruses.
In these instances, it would be necessary to set a theoretical
upper limit of contamination and hence a desirable overall virus
reduction factor which would incorporate a safety margin to take
account of factors such as differences between the scale down and
manufacturing plant and differences between model and relevant
viruses. In such cases it is recommended that the purification
process should have at least one stage which gives a clearance of
at least 105 for viruses of direct concern, and an overall
clearance sufficient to include a high margin of safety if
possible. </p>
<p align="center">&#160;</p>
<table width="100%">
    <tr>
        <td width="50%"> 
