<html>
<head>
<title>Managed Care - What does it mean?</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body background="images/backgrnd.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
link="#000080">
<h2 align="center"><u><MAP NAME="FrontPageMap"><AREA SHAPE="RECT" COORDS="2, 3, 103, 37" HREF="INDEX.HTM"></MAP><a
href="/corningb/_vti_map/healecon.htm.map"><img align="bottom"
src="IMAGES/home.gif" width="104" ismap usemap="#FrontPageMap"
height="38" border="0"></a></u></h2>
<h2 align="center"><u><img src="IMAGES/cps2.gif" align="bottom"
width="306" height="45"></u></h2>
<h2><u>MANAGED CARE - What Does It Mean?</u></h2>
<p><strong>Tony Lockett, Head of </strong><a href="HEALTH.HTM"><strong>Health
Economics</strong></a><strong>, Corning Besselaar, Maidenhead UK</strong></p>
<h3><u>Introduction </u></h3>
<p>Managed care is an often quoted but misunderstood term. It is
used as a &quot;cover all&quot; term for a range of health
delivery services, which seeks to manage the care received by
consumers. This in contrast to fee for service (FFS) systems
where the care is unmanaged. More recently managed care systems
have become synonymous with the range of tools used to control
utilisation of services by consumers and manage the practice of
the health professionals offering care.<br>
Managed care first started in the US health care system, where
purchasers and payers sought methods to control expenditure.
Managed care systems are now employed by all health maintenance
organisations (HMOs) and preferred provider organisations (PPOs)
in the USA. Indeed it has been said that HMOs grew out of the
need to manage health care resources. The approaches taken y
these organisations to manage health care resources have one or
more of the following features:</p>
<ul>
    <li>a hierarchical, vertically integrated structure.</li>
    <li>financial incentives that involve showing risk.</li>
    <li>a series of utilisation controls.</li>
</ul>
<p>These features are usually manifest as a move from payment on
a fee for services basis to payment for package of care, or
payment for a flat fee or capitation for the total care of a
patient.</p>
<h3>Managed care in the US </h3>
<p>The introduction of managed care into US health care has been
part of a revolutionary change which has occurred during the last
20 years. In the 1960s the majority of Americans were covered by
private insurance. Under this system care was paid for under a
'Fee For Service' and providers of care were more or less free to
give any treatment at any cost. The government sponsored the
health care for those who could not afford it under Medicare (for
the disabled and elderly) an Medicaid (for the poor)<a
href="#Gabel J., Jajich-Toth C., De-Lissoroy G., Rice, T., Cohen H., The changing world of group health insurance. Health Affairs 1988: (Summer).">2</a></p>
<p>Into this system European immigrants introduced pre-paid group
practices, to resemble the sick funds seen in continental Europe.
HMOs, as these organisations were subsequently rechristened, have
gradually become a major model in the delivery of US health care,
and by the late 1980s over 50% of Americans were enrolled in HMO
plan. HMOs are responsible for managing a fixed amount of money
to provide health care to a determined population. They do this
by a variety of contractual agreements with providers of care.<a
href="#Gabel J., Jajich-Toth C., De-Lissoroy G., Rice, T., Cohen H., The changing world of group health insurance. Health Affairs 1988: (Summer).">2</a><br>
There are several types of HMO. The earliest version was the
staff model, where a group of physicians would care for a single
HMO's patients. In this situation the medical staff are usually
salaried employees of HMO. A variation on this is the group model
where groups of doctors remain an independent legal body and
serve an HMO on a fee for services basis.<br>
Another model for HMO structure is the individual physician
association (IPA). Originally, as the name suggests, IPA models
were made up of solo practitioners contracting on a fee for
service basis. This model of HMO has now evolved into a network
of care model. They are the most numerous type of HMO seen in the
USA and account for 78% of the HMOs.<a
href="#Weiner J.P., Ferris D.M., GP budget holding in the UK, lessons from America. Kings Fund Institute Research Report 7, 1990.">1</a><br>
Outside the managed care plans offered by HMOs other arrangements
have evolved to offer managed care. These include the plans
described below.</p>
<p><em><strong>Preferred provider organisations (PPO) </strong></em><br>
Where there is a 'broker' acting between the purchasers and
providers of care. The providers of care are still charging a fee
for service basis.</p>
<p><em><strong>Competitive medical plans (CMP) </strong></em><br>
A plan where there are capitation payments made to providers of
care, based on the average cost of treatment per head and risk
sharing agreement. These plans differ from HMOs as they are not
federally regulated.</p>
<p><em><strong>Health insurance organisations (HIO)</strong></em> <br>
These organisations contract with Medicaid to provide care. They
do not offer care themselves, but contract with providers.</p>
<p><em><strong>Managed indemnity plans (MIP) </strong></em><br>
Private insurance companies offering managed care programs for
enrolees, paid for by fee for service.</p>
<p><em><strong>Tripe option plans (TOP) </strong></em></p>
<p>Plans offering the option of HMO, PPO and MIP</p>
<h2>The pros and cons of managed care </h2>
<p>The basic assumption underlying managed care is that the
process will manage health care resources more efficiently than
individual decision making. If this is to be the case then in
addition to sound theoretical frameworks more concrete skills are
needed. These skills include financial, contracting, human
resources and actuarial skills.<br>
The issues thrown up by a move to managed care are complex. They
can be broken down into re-imbursement/capitation problems,
risks, information systems, management, accounting, pharmacy,
conflicts of interest and equity.</p>
<p><strong><u>Reimbursement/capitation</u></strong> <br>
As identified earlier, most managed care systems have a fixed
budget to purchase health care for this population. In order to
maximise the use of their budget the organisations spend on a
capitation, not fee for service basis. This implies that the
organisation offers a set amount of resource for every patient in
its list to the providers of care. Most managed care capitation
is based on age and sex. Studies have shown that demographic
variables such as deprivation scores, make little difference to
the resource use. However, the incorporation of previous service
use and population morbidity measures increase the value of
capitation formulae.<br>
It is likely that no formula can predict the total amount of
resources consumed or committed to the care of patients. The most
sophisticated formula developed, including previous use and
mobidity factors, only predicts 50% of the expenditure per
person. This has considerable influence on the role of risk
management in managed care.3</p>
<p><strong><u>Risk management</u></strong> <br>
The development of a managed care system involves the
establishment and management of risk pools. The size of these
pools is determined by actuarial derived formulae to calculate
the outgoing claims.<br>
In managed care in the USA the risk of pools are often split into
an overall pool and a physician pool. The overall pool is a
measure of the total risk, while the physician pool is the risk
attributable to an individual physician. While it is generally
accepted that the overall pool must be fairly large, the size of
the physician pool is open to question. The physician pool
provides a major incentive to the behaviour of HMO-contracted
medical care. As an empirical rule, the individual pool should be
larger then 300 patients.1</p>
<p><strong><u>Managed information system (MIS)</u></strong> <br>
Information is the element needed in all health care systems.
However, information systems are complex and expensive to
administer, as well as being time-consuming to develop. Despite
these problems, experience with managed care has suggested that
the pre-requisite for success is the information systems. In
studies of network HMOs the major determinate of stability was
the size of the enrolment pool, then the information system. MIS
has been referred to as the glue that holds managed care together<a
href="#Weiner J.P., Ferris D.M., GP budget holding in the UK, lessons from America. Kings Fund Institute Research Report 7, 1990.">.1</a></p>
<p><strong><u>Management expertise </u></strong><br>
The HMO model in the USA has demonstrated that expertise in
accounting, human resources, information technology, quality and
negotiation are all essential in the success of managed care
organisation. However, these skills do not come cheap, and
management overheads for managed care organisations are high.1</p>
<p><strong><u>Accounting problems </u></strong><br>
Although there are general accounting needs in managed care,
there are also specific ones. A major problem is the 'incurred by
not reported expenditure' or IBNR. IBNR occurs because of the
backlog and time delays between expenditure being incurred and
appearing in the financial statements. Thus, organisations maybe
incurring massive debts when it is being reported that the
organisation is in profit. This is generally handled by the
construction of lag schedules.1</p>
<p><strong><u>Pharmacy services </u></strong><br>
Managed care programmes have had considerable impact in
increasing the amount of expenditure devolved to pharmacy
budgets. In response to this increase, changes have been made to
prescribing controls. One of these has been the development of
drug utilisation reviews and clinical guidelines. Also, most
managed care groups mandate generic substitution and a few have
developed practice formulas. One more extreme measure involves
the practice of therapeutic substitution. This involves a
pharmacist being given the ability to substitute classes of drugs
on the grounds of efficiency or effectiveness. Other
controversial measures include types of patient controls, for
example, limited quantities of drugs or the use of trial doses.
These measures are believed to reduce waste, although evidence is
scant.1</p>
<p><strong><u>Quality assurance (QA) </u></strong><br>
Quality assurance is one of the major strengths of the HMO system
in the USA. Particular emphasis is placed on the role of QA in
improving the effectiveness and efficiency of care. Therefore the
quality assurance programme is usually extensive and based about
six key steps:</p>
<ol>
    <li>Identification of problems.</li>
    <li>Establishment of measurable criteria.</li>
    <li>Data Collection.</li>
    <li>Identification of a strategic direction.</li>
    <li>Introduction of Improvements.</li>
    <li>Re-monitoring.</li>
</ol>
<p>The focus of much of the QA activity has been on primary care.
It is very common in a typical HMO of 50,000 individuals that
monthly audit of 30 patients in a specific issue are examined.
The QA aspects of managed care are continually under review.
Recent developments have included:</p>
<ul>
    <li>The incorporation of quality into MIS</li>
    <li>The development of community and population QA measures.
        i.e. 'list' not individual measures.</li>
    <li>The adaptation of industrial models of QA.<a
        href="#Weiner J.P., Ferris D.M., GP budget holding in the UK, lessons from America. Kings Fund Institute Research Report 7, 1990.">1</a></li>
</ul>
<p><strong><u>Equity </u></strong></p>
<p>HMOs have identified problems in delivering care to those
individuals of lower social classes. This led to the suggestion
that managed care programmes may be inequitable. In attempts to
address this issue many HMOs are looking at delivery mechanisms
to lower classes, which may avoid physician care.</p>
<p><strong><u>Conflict of interest </u></strong><br>
One of the major concerns about managed care models is that there
is evidence emerging from the USA that they heighten the clash of
interests between insurers and physicians. This centres on the
use of protocols to deny treatment to expensive patients, in the
interest of the HMO and physicians reducing the care to complex
patients in order to maximise profits. This problem is so acute
that federal regulations are being proposed.</p>
<p><strong><u>Models of managed care </u></strong><br>
In the light of the need to deliver health care, managed care has
developed two major models as follows:</p>
<ul>
    <li><em><strong>Macro managed care models </strong></em><br>
        These are models designed to cross the primary and
        secondary care interface. They would cover, for instance,
        the hospitalisation drug therapy and home care for a
        surgical patient.</li>
    <li><br>
        <em><strong>Micro models of managed care </strong></em><br>
        These focus on specific areas, such as the control of
        primary care drug prescribing, or asthma care. They cover
        areas such as prescribing, practice nursing care,
        education with the aim of improving quality and cost
        containment.<br>
        Both of these models are widely employed in the USA.</li>
</ul>
<h2><u>Managed care in the UK </u></h2>
<p>Managed care has been lifted up the health care agenda as a
result of EL 94(94).<a href="#Epstein A">4</a><br>
This EL was in response to the increasing number of approaches
being made by drug companies and HMOs to DHAs in the UK.
Referring to disease management packages and discounted drug
prices, it urged caution. Despite the letter, many DHAs are
looking at managed care to make better use of resources. Indeed
some authorities have said that one of the few ways to make
primary care-led purchasing really effective would be to
introduce managed care. However, the HS, set up as it was as a
social system, presents considerable barriers to the introduction
of this process.</p>
<p>Foremost in many peoples' mind would be problems associated
with corporate governance. The NHS has recently been rocked by
many scandals involving the supply of services, most notably
computer services. The idea of entering into partnership with
commercial companies, which in some ways may involve the
exclusive use of products and services does not sit easily with
many people.</p>
<p>If the problem of governance could be overcome there are a
number of practical issues to consider. The first of these would
be the availability of information to develop and maintain the
care. Medical records are confidential and there is some debate
about the legality of external agencies auditing them In addition
to this, much of the information is not available, especially in
community care.</p>
<p>The gaps in information are compounded by the lack of
information on performance measurement in primary care. It is
unclear what drives primary care performance and until clearer
measures are available managed care becomes difficult.<br>
The current tendering regulation also presents barriers to the
introduction of managed care. Currently it is required that
non-clinical contracts in excess of &#163;140,000 should be
tendered (this is currently under review). Therefore it is likely
that if DHAs wanted to introduce managed care these services
would have to be tendered for. This would be a problem in cases
where drug companies wanted to introduce care.</p>
<p>Managed care is also in conflict with much of the performance
measurement applied to DHAs at present. The development of risk
management requires, for effective enforcement, the ability of
DHAs to make savings and deficits, currently not allowed. Managed
care may also inflate pharmacy budgets at the expense of hospital
care budgets. This would cause problems with the current drive on
prescribing costs. The development of managed care would also
cause problems with the efficiency index which monitors
purchasers. It is likely that managed care would shift resources
away from FCEs, unacceptable at the current time of monitoring
local services by the number of patients treated.<br>
This shift would cause further problems in withdrawing funding
from acute hospitals, possibly leading to hospital closure.<br>
<br>
These problems would have most impact on the macro models of
managed care. They would appear to offer few obstacles to micro
models. However, it has been argued that at present there is
little need for micro models in the UK. Most of the techniques
used by micro models are already standard practice. The use of
generic prescribing, and reducing prescribing amounts are already
widely used. It is also known that prescribing costs are already
low in the UK. So the benefits from micro models would be
considerably reduced when compared with the USA.</p>
<p>One possible solution to these problems would be to develop
provider based managed care models, which the provider of care
can then market. If these were to be NHS Trusts then many of the
immediate problems would be solved. It would like to provider
performance, and solve the issues of reduction in acute
contracts.</p>
<h2><u>Conclusion </u></h2>
<p>Managed care has been used for the USA for many years. Some of
the features have been introduced into the UK system already and
if the development is to continue then changes in the regulatory
structure are required.</p>
<h2><u>References </u></h2>
<ol>
    <li><a
        name="Weiner J.P., Ferris D.M., GP budget holding in the UK, lessons from America. Kings Fund Institute Research Report 7, 1990.">Weiner
        J.P., Ferris D.M., GP budget holding in the UK, lessons
        from America. Kings Fund Institute Research Report 7,
        1990.</a></li>
    <li><a
        name="Gabel J., Jajich-Toth C., De-Lissoroy G., Rice, T., Cohen H., The changing world of group health insurance. Health Affairs 1988: (Summer).">Gabel
        J., Jajich-Toth C., De-Lissoroy G., Rice, T., Cohen H.,
        The changing world of group health insurance. Health
        Affairs 1988: (Summer).</a></li>
    <li><a name="Epstein A">Epstein A</a>., Cumella F.,
        Capitation payments. Using predictors of medical
        utilisation to adjust rates. Health Care Financing Review
        1988 (Autumn): 51-69.</li>
    <li><a name="EL9">EL9</a>4(94) Department of Health, 1995.</li>
</ol>
<p>&#160;</p>
