</DOCHDR>
<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Comments in Support of the IIA Act</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<body BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" link="#2F4F2F" vlink="#3232CD">
<CENTER><FONT SIZE=5 color="#2F4F2F"><a name="atr">Comments</a> in Support of the<br>
Individual Investment Account Act<br>
(S. 159 and H.R. 328)<br></FONT></CENTER>
<HR>
<P>
<CENTER><FONT SIZE=4>Grover G. Norquist, President<br>
Americans for Tax Reform, Washington, D.C.<br></FONT></CENTER>
<P>
&quot;The right to pursue personal liberty, opportunity and economic prosperity is the promise of America.  To create new jobs and increase the standard of living for all, we must relieve the punitive tax burden on productive Americans who invest in their fellow men.  Tragically, the existing U.S. tax code penalizes this investment and thereby forestalls economic growth.<br> 
<p>
The Individual Investment Account (IIA) Act corrects this serious flaw - attacks code which has increasingly robbed America of greater GDP growth, new jobs, increased living standards, and even government tax receipts.<br>
<p>
Succinctly, IIAs allow unlimited, fully tax-deductible contributions to IRA-type accounts.  All investment activity is tax free until withdrawn by the saver or beneficiary, thereby eliminating redundant taxation on the same capital.  With IIAs, there are no penalty taxes, no forced distributions, nor estate taxes.<br>
<p>
This common sense bipartisan legislation is the springboard to an American economic renaissance.  All members of Congress, and their constituents, should actively urge its enactment.&quot;<br>
<p>
<HR WIDTH=75% ALIGN=center SIZE=3>
<p>
<CENTER><FONT SIZE=4><a name="sbsc">Karen Kerrigan, President</a><br>
Small Business Survival Committee, Washington, D.C.<br></FONT></CENTER>
<P>
&quot;America's small business is the powerful economic engine that innovates, creates jobs and spurs economic growth.  The vital fuel for this engine is capital.  Capital is derived from the accumulated and ongoing savings and investments of people.  In fact, there is no other source.<br>
<p>
The existing income tax as applied to personal saving and investing is severely biased against saving and investing.  The effect of this nonsensical bias compounds over time thereby progressively curtailing all economic growth -- and particularly so the job creating growth of small businesses and entrepreneurs.<br>
<p>
The Individual Investment Account Act simply and effectively strips away this tax bias against saving and investing.  IIAs are IRA-type plans that allow each person to contribute unlimited, fully tax-deductible amounts.  Investment activity accumulates tax free until withdrawn by the owner or the beneficiary.  There are no penalty taxes, or forced distributions, nor estate taxes upon death.<br>
<p>
The SBSC urges all voters and their respective members of Congress to actively support this extremely important remedial legislation.&quot;<br>
<p>
<HR WIDTH=75% ALIGN=center SIZE=3>
<p>
<CENTER><FONT SIZE=4><a name="cato">Stephen Moore, Director of Fiscal Policy Studies</a><br>
CATO Institute, Washington, D.C.<br></FONT></CENTER>
<P>
&quot;I looked through the proposed savings plan of Senator Breaux and Representative McCrery<br>
[S. 159 &amp; H.R. 328] and agree with its content entirely.<br>
<P>
No country can grow and prosper without a healthy savings rate.  There is a very simple way to raise savings and investment in America.  It is to remove the tax bias against savings by allowing taxpayers unlimited annual contributions to IRA-type plans.<br>
<p>
Several reputable studies have shown conclusively that IRAs in their current form increase personal savings. Removing the caps and expanding the eligibility for tax deductible saving could double America's savings rate overnight.&quot;<br>
<p>
<HR WIDTH=75% ALIGN=center SIZE=3>
<p>
<CENTER><FONT SIZE=4><a name="accf">Mark Bloomfield, President </a><br>
and<br>
Margo Thorning, Chief Economist<br>
American Council for Capital Formation, Washington, D.C.<br></FONT></CENTER>
<P>
&quot;The ACCF supports IRA-type plans such as those in this Act as a way of encouraging the savings necessary for increased investment.  High levels of investment, particularly in productive equipment, is a key element in increasing U.S. economic growth.  S. 159 and H.R. 328, which provide an unlimited tax deduction for saving and eliminate penalty taxes and forced distributions, could make a significant contribution to our economic future.&quot;<br>
<p>
<HR WIDTH=75% ALIGN=center SIZE=3>
<p>
<CENTER><FONT SIZE=4><a name="uscc">Dr. Richard Rahn</a><br>
Former Vice President and Chief Economist of the<br>
Chamber of Commerce of the United States<br>
</FONT></CENTER>
<P>
&quot;As has long been recognized, the United States suffers from a low level of new capital formation which in turn has depressed economic growth.  This lack of capital formation is mainly a result of the U.S. tax code being far more biased against productive saving and investment than our foreign competitors face in their tax laws.  Senator John Breaux and Representative Jim McCrery propose to eliminate much of this tax bias [via the] Individual Investment Account Act, which would establish universal, unlimited, tax deductible IRA-type plans.<br>
<p>
Those members of Congress who are truly committed to reigniting economic growth in America, creating millions of productive new jobs, and reducing poverty and increasing economic opportunity and prosperity, will support this needed legislation.<br>
<p>
There will be those who say it will favor the rich, but they will ignore the fact that a rich man can only benefit from the legislation by productively investing his money and refraining from consumption.  As a result, this investment will create jobs for poor men.<br>
<p>
There will be those who say this legislation will add to the federal deficit.  Such an argument ignores the reality that the federal deficit is in large part a result of too little economic growth, and of increased demand for government support by people without jobs or economic opportunity.  Expanding IRA-type plans over the long run will reduce the federal deficit by increasing jobs, total wage payments, and payroll taxes, and diminishing the need for government payments as a result of expanded economic opportunity.&quot;<br>
<p>
<hr>
[<a href="/savers/">Home</a>]<br>
<font size=2>Savers &amp; Investors League, September 1996</font><br>
</body>
</HTML>
