</DOCHDR>
<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>The Right Tax Plan For Dole </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>

<B>Investor's Business Daily</B>
<br>
Wednesday, July 17, 1996<br>
<hr>
<center>
<font size=5>GUEST EDITORIAL<br>
<hr>
<i>The Right Tax Plan For Dole</i></font><br>
By VICTOR A. CANTO<br>
</center>
<blockquote>
<p>
Less than a month before the Republican Convention, Bob Dole has yet to present a tax-cut plan.  Why?  Most likely because he hasn't seen one he likes.  The answer may be an unlimited, front-loaded individual retirement account.
<p>
Everyone expects a Republican candidate to set down a tax-cut plan.  And, aside from naming a running mate, a tax cut is Dole's best chance for a fresh, strong appeal to the voters.  But he needs a plan that makes economic sense, wins support within his party and in the country at large and also fits with the Dole we all know.
<p>
The right IRA reforms fill that bill.  They would open a new opportunity for all Americans to save, boosting our national rates of saving and investing, and thus economic growth.  The plan would promote economic efficiency by taxing each economic transaction only once and by end-running the job-killing capital gains tax.
<p>
Early in the campaign, Dole commissioned a group headed by Jack Kemp to draw up a tax plan for the future.  Kemp landed on a refined version of the Hall-Rabushka flat tax.  Dole balked at that, though he has supported a flatter tax structure over the years.
<p>
Kemp then threw his support to Steve Forbes, who based his surprisingly successful campaign on the flat tax.  But when Forbes left the race, so too did the flat tax.
<p>
An unlimited, front-loaded IRA plan can reap some of the benefits of a flat tax - but has stronger political &quot;wings.&quot  It would increase our nation's savings rate and also free up cash trapped in slow-performing investments.
<p>
Current law limits each of us to a maximum IRA contribution of $2,000 a year.  Income taxes don't apply to the money paid into the fund, but do to the money withdrawn from it.
<p>
The $2,000 limit is an arbitrary figure.  Raising it - increasing the chance for tax-deferred investment - would likely boost our national savings rate, which many analysts say is too low.  Removing the limit altogether should boost the savings rate considerably.
<p>
But IRAs are limited for a reason: the fear that, given the chance, too many people would defer too many taxes for too many years.  The loss of tax revenues, though temporary, would seem to increase the federal budget deficit.
<p>
We can solve that problem by front-loading the IRA - by taxing money as it goes into the fund, not as it is withdrawn.
<p>
Think of the tax on IRAs as a sales tax - a tax that is levied when people spend money, rather than when they earn it.  A tax imposed at the end of the time of possession is said to be &quot;back-loaded.&quot;
<p>
A front-loaded tax, by contrast, resembles an income tax, levied when people earn money.  The tax is levied as money is placed into the account, not when it is removed.
<p>
The two taxes generate equivalent amounts of revenue for the government - but the timing of the actual tax receipts is quite different.  Front-loading generates revenue sooner, back-loading later.
<p>
Either way, the program delivers the same amount to the saver at retirement.
<p>
The government could generate extra tax revenues by adding one more twist: allowing all current IRA holders to convert their accounts to the new program.  this would generate a one-time revenue windfall.
<p>
The unlimited, front-loaded IRA indirectly addresses another issue dear to Republican hearts; the capital gains tax.
<p>
The plan adheres to the single taxation philosophy.  Under it, all income earned on the IRA would be tax-free.  The sale of assets in the account would also be tax-free, provided the proceeds are reinvested in the IRA.
<p>
The unlimited IRA is a way to prospectively unlock capital gains and allow for a more efficient resource allocation.  And the &quot;front-loading&quot; feature avoids the need to index gains for inflation, because gains within the retirement account would be liquidated without additional taxes.
<p>
In short, the unlimited, front-loaded IRA provides a way to defuse the capital gains issue, while delivering most of the benefits of single taxation and indexation.
<p>
In is also a way to help each American save for his or her own retirement - a cause Bob Dole can support with real enthusiasm.
<p>
</blockquote>
<hr>
<i>Victor A. Canto is partner in the economic consulting firm A.B. Laffer, V.A. Canto &amp; Associates.</i>
<hr>
[<a href="/savers/">Home</a>]


</BODY>
</HTML>
