<HTML>

<HEAD><title>Summary Statement</title>
</HEAD>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<center>
<font size=4><b><a name="top">Summary</a> Statement of W. Thomas Kelly, President<br>
SAVERS &amp; INVESTORS LEAGUE</b></font><br>
<font size=3><b>Before the Ways &amp; Means Committee<br>
U.S. House of Representatives<br>
on<br>
January 31, 1995</b></font><br>
</center>
<hr>
Mr. Chairman, and members of the Committee, I thank you for inviting
me to comment on those provisions of the Contract With America
that are designed to encourage savings and investment.  The League's
views may be summarized by three important points.
<p>
<b><center>Our First Important Point:</b></center> 
<p>
First, we support the Contract's American Dream Savings
Account provision.  It is certainly a move in the right direction.
However, in our view, these provisions do not go far enough.
Legislation should be adopted promptly to fully remove the ordinary
income tax bias against saving.  
<P>
This cancerous tax bias is a constant, progressive drain on the
fiscal soundness of our government and on the economic growth
of our nation.  This tax bias must be removed- totally.
<P>
This total removal is accomplished by (1) allowing unlimited
tax deductions and tax deferrals for IRA-type saving; (2) income
taxes would be imposed only upon any plan withdrawal at then existing
progressive tax rates, like wages; and (3) there would be no penalty
taxes nor forced distribution at any age.  
<P>
These three, simple, basic criteria are embodied in the bipartisan
Individual Investment Account Act of 1995 (H.R. 328), as sponsored
by Mr. McCrery of this Committee, and S. 159 sponsored by Senator
Breaux of the Finance Committee.
<p>
<b><center>Our Second Important Point:</b></center>
<p>
Our second important point is that no consideration of
how to improve our nation's rate of saving can ignore the staff
procedures for measuring the alleged &quot;tax expenditure costs&quot;
of IRAs.  These staff procedures are so flawed that the Committee's
tax policy considerations are seriously compromised.  
<P>
Even the Treasury Department's 1995 Budget document, for the
first time ever, disclosed that its tax expenditure figures for
IRAs were overstated by over three times when measured on a more
rational, realistic basis.  And, even these severely reduced costs
continue to reflect the self-defeating second layer of tax on
saving that should not be imposed upon our government, our taxpayers,
and our nation.
<P>
Much debate arises over static vs. dynamic scoring of the alleged
costs of IRA-type plans.  Static scoring stands logic and sound
tax policy on its head.  For example, it assumes that IRA tax
deductions are an expense rather than creating a government asset.
The dynamic scoring of IRAs is fiscally sound and entirely proper.
<P>
The dynamic scoring of H.R. 328 by well-respected economists
show that tax receipts grow quickly, and become progressively
larger each year over those otherwise collected under the ordinary
income tax.  
<P>
These increasing tax receipts reflect the growth in saving, in
production, in GDP and in jobs; and the resulting reduction in
the cost of capital brought about by unlimited, tax-deductible
saving.  
 
<P>
And, because the gains arising from increased capital flow
in very large measure to labor, it is estimated that unlimited,
tax-deductible saving will increase the after-tax income
of <I>all</I> middle-income taxpayers by 12% to 23% within six
or seven years following enactment.
<p>
<b><center>Our Third Important Point:</b></center>
<p> 
Our third important point is to recognize that unlimited,
tax-deductible IRA-type plans are <I>not</I> tax loopholes for
the rich.  The full removal of the income tax bias against saving
not only restores the taxation of saving to one of proper neutrality
in terms of saving vs. consumption, it is also neutral in regards
to the taxation of realized capital gain vs. dividends or interest
income.
<P>
Unlimited, tax-deductible, tax-deferred saving is not
a favoring of savers in any tax bracket; it is solely one of restoring
fiscally sound tax neutrality at all tax brackets.
<p>
<center><b>Summary</b></center>

<P>
In summary, the removal of only a portion of the tax bias
against saving, as found in the American Dream Savings Account
legislation, is only a partial correction of the tax bias
against saving when a full correction is both imperative
and sound.
<P>
The unlimited, tax-deductible Individual Investment Accounts of
H.R. 328 are tax revenue gainers, not losers. Thus, there is no reason, other than 
an irrational, existing staff scoring dogma, to deny our nation, including
all taxpayers and our government, the singular advantages
that will flow from this sound legislation.
<P>
The League urges the Committee to thoroughly explore the economic
growth and rational tax revenue implications of H.R. 328.
<P>
[<a href="/savers/">Home</a>], [<a href="/savers/library.html">Library</a>]
</BODY>

