2040       (1115)         1571           456              124        5661
2060       (4314)         6677          2363              164        6297
<hr></pre>   
<h6> *The net present-value calculations
assume a discount rate of 11.6 percent-the estimated rate of return to society
given by a long-term return on mutual funds.  This study was prepared in 1993 and
published in Wealth Is Not A Dirty Word, Mill Run Press, P aoli, PA.  The swing
(i.e., loss to gain) in estimated revenues (b-a) is mind boggling (e.g., $136
billion in year 2000)! 
</h6>
The government measures tax revenue on the unrealistic &quot;static&quot; basis
shown above, i.e., the government assumes people don't change their actions when
tax laws are changed, and ignores expanded tax collections from a soundly growing
economy.  [R emember how a static estimate raised taxes on boats, thereby killing
hobs and losing tax revenue?] The &quot;dynamic&quot; basis reflects the realistic
fact that people respond to tax law changes.  In this case, new net saving will
grow dramatically. 
<p>
Increased saving, created by unlimited, tax-deductible IRAs would increase
production, increase jobs, reduce interest costs, and increase tax revenue. 
Taxpayers after-tax income (and related standard of living) by the year 
2000 would be increased as shown in Table 2. </PRE>
<p>
<center><H3>Table 2</H3>
<p>

