<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Save Our Savings</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<CENTER><FONT SIZE=5><b>&quot;Save Our Savings&quot;</b></FONT><BR>
by Tom Kelly<BR>
<HR>
<FONT SIZE=2>As printed in the <I>Free Press</I>, Quakertown, PA<BR>
August 6, 1993<BR></FONT>
<HR>
</CENTER>
<P>
Congress, as well as the current (and former) Administration, feel compelled to raise taxes,
coupled with illusionary spending cuts.  Voter/taxpayers are sick and tired, to the point of
revulsion, of the hackneyed demagoguery that always accompanies every budget debate.
  The claim is always made that the sky will fall unless taxes are raised.  Don't elected officials 
ever feel sick from being forced to participate in such a mindless exercise?
<P>
Grass roots voter/taxpayers are awakening to the fact that raising taxes has never, repeat never, cut
 our nation's deficit or debt.  Surely, members of Congress must know this, too.  As all Americans 
with common sense know, only enhanced private saving and private enterprise, coupled with 
governmental spending restraint, can reduce our nation's true deficit and debt.  Federal taxes are not only far too high, they impose a double, even triple tax on saving.
<P>
It is time for every member of Congress, as the elected representative of his or her constituents, to break away from the arcane and incredibly erroneous governmental revenue estimations that have no credibility whatsoever, except among
government people.  They blithely forecast deficit and debt reduction, when realism shows the exact
opposite.  Every member's vote on this important budget and tax matter should reflect plain common sense, not a blind 
acceptance of budgetary legerdemain that cannot be explained nor defended to constituents.
<P>
Regardless of party affiliation, a vote for common sense budget policy will: (a) reject the 
present budget package; and (b) subsequently focus on real, current spending cuts
 and a tax and budget policy that will enhance personal saving and investment, not destroy them.
<P>
It's important to recognize that when people save (regardless of tax bracket), they are placing their savings on the marketplace for others to use. 
 Obviously, the others (in all walks of life and in all tax brackets) who use this saving expect to profit therefrom, while paying for its use.  The 
dynamics of such &quot;free market&quot; capitalism builds upon itself.  
This is what makes nations prosper, 
thereby creating real jobs at all levels.  Clearly, saving should only be taxed once - when it's 
consumed (spent).
<P>
Thus, taxing such saving before it is consumed not only destroys the taxpayers' return, it removes badly needed 
private capital from the marketplace, thereby concurrently destroying the 
government's &quot;private savings&quot; tax base as
 well.  This is a surefire recipe for gradual economic strangulation, not only at the personal and family 
levels, but at the national level as well.
<P>
Our nation is now feeling the ever-tightening economic noose around its neck.
<p>    
<hr>      
[<a href="/savers/">Home</a>],  [<a href="/savers/library.html">Library</a>] 
<br>
<font size=1>Savers &amp; Investors League, 1995</font>      

</BODY>
</HTML>
