<html>
<head><title>Summary - USA Tax</title></head>
<body>
<center>
<font size=5><b>
USA TAX - Summary<br></font>
<font size=4>S.722<br> 
</b></font>
<hr>
(This analysis is an excerpt from &quot;A Side By Side Analysis Of Alternative Tax System Proposals&quot;  
published August 1, 1995 by <a href="/savers/legislation/blc.html">The Business 
Leadership Council</a>.)  
  </center>
<hr>
<b>Sponsors:</b> Mr. Domenici and Mr. Nunn  
  <p>
<b>Basic Principles:</b>  The bill imposes a steeply graduated consumed 
income tax on individuals.  It imposes   
a subtraction method value added tax on business.  The proposal would have a fairly comprehensive   
consumption tax base but would retain a reduced mortgage interest deduction, a charitable deduction and   
enact a deduction for higher educational expenses.  The proposal would provide a credit to employers and   
employees for FICA taxes paid and an earned income tax credit.  The proposal would have a consumption   
tax base, but the exceptions are significant.  
  <p>
<b>Rate Structure, Individuals: </b> Different tax tables apply for each of 
the years 1996 to 1999, inclusive.  For all years, the top rate is 40 
percent of taxable income.  The 1996 tax tables are: <br> 
  <p>
For married filing jointly and surviving spouses:  <br>
<p>  
$0-$5,399 :     19%  <br>
$5,400 to $24,000 :    $1,026 plus 27%  <br>
Over $24,000 :           $6,048 plus 40%  <br>
  <p>
For heads of household:  
 <p> 
$0-$4,749 :    19%  <br>
$4,750 to $21,100 :   $903 plus 27%  <br>
Over $21,100 :          $5,317 plus 40%  <br>
  <p>
For unmarried individuals:  
  <p>
$0-$3,199 :   19% <br> 
$3,200 to $14,400 :   $608 plus 27%  <br>
Over $14,400 :          $3,632 plus 40%  <br>
  <p>
For married couples filing separately:  
  <p>
$0-$2,699 :   19%  <br>
$2,700 to $12,000 :   $513 plus 27%  <br>
Over $12,000 :          $3,024 plus 40%  <br>
  <p>
<b>Tax Base, Generally:</b>  The individual tax base would include 
compensation,  most fringe benefits,   
dividends, interest, rents, royalties and other capital income, capital gains and certain other income.    
Gifts, municipal bond interest and certain other income would be excluded from the tax base.  Mortgage   
interest on acquisition indebtedness, certain higher education expense and certain charitable contributions   
would be deductible.  Net savings would generally be deductible.  Net dissavings would generally be   
taxable.  
  <p>
<b>Interest, Dividends and Other Investment Income and Expense:</b>  
Interest, royalties, dividends, annuity   
payments, income from life insurance, endowment contracts, distributive share of partnership income (or   
loss) from intangible property and similar investment income would be included in gross income and   
subject to tax.  However, if the income was reinvested (in the sense that the taxpayer increased net   
savings), the taxpayer would receive a deduction and the tax would be deferred.  
  <p>
<b>Municipal Bond Interest:</b>  Municipal bond interest would not be 
taxable.  
  <p>
<b>Standard Deduction Family Living Allowance:</b>  The family living 
allowance (equivalent of a standard   deduction) would be:  
  <p>
$7,400 for a joint return or a surviving spouse;<br>  
$5,400 for a head of household;  <br>
$4,400 for a single person;  <br>
$3,700 for a married couple filing separately.<br>  
  <p>
<b>Personal Exemption:</b>  $2,550 per person.  
  <p>
<b>Dependent Exemption:</b>  $2,550 per dependent.  
  <p>
<b>Capital Gains:</b>  Included in gross income.  However, if the income was 
reinvested (in the sense that the   
taxpayer increased net savings), the taxpayer would receive a deduction and the tax would be deferred.  
  <p>
<b>Home Ownership:</b>  The home mortgage interest deduction is curtailed 
but retained.  Only acquisition   
indebtedness (but not home equity loan) interest would be deductible.  Tax-free rollover of primary   
residence retained.  Capital gains from the sale of a primary residence are taxed.  However, if the proceeds   
were saved, the tax would be deferred.  
  <p>
<b>State and Local Taxes: </b> Generally not deductible.  
  <p>
<b>Estate and Gift Taxes:</b>  The unified estate and gift tax is retained.  
  <p>
<b>Pensions, IRAs and Other Qualified Plans:</b>  All existing rules 
relating to pensions and qualified plans   
are repealed.  Net savings are deductible and the tax deferred until the taxpayer has net dissavings.   
  <p>
<b>Compensation (Wages & Salaries):</b>  Compensation would be taxable to 
individuals.  Compensation   would not be deductible to businesses.  
  <p>
<b>Charitable Contributions:</b>  Charitable deductions would generally be 
allowed up to 50 percent of a   taxpayers adjusted gross income.  
  <p>
<b>Educational Expenses: </b> A deduction of up to $2,000 per year per 
student for certain higher educational   expenses is allowed.  
  <p>
<b>Savings, Generally:</b>  The return to savings would be taxed unless 
saved.  The taxpayer would be afforded   
a deduction equal to his net savings.  Generally, net savings is the excess, if any, of additions to savings   
over taxable withdrawals from savings.  If taxable withdrawals exceed additions to savings, the net   
withdrawal is included in the taxpayers taxable income.  Savings are broadly defined to include most   
financial assets but exclude collectibles.  
  <p>
<b>Inflation Indexing:</b>  The family living allowance, personal exemptions 
and tax brackets are indexed for   inflation.  
  <p>
<b>Social Security Benefits:</b>  Social Security benefits are fully taxable.
<p>
<hr>
[<a href="/savers/">Home</a>], Legislation Listed By: [<a 
href="/savers/legnum.html">Bill No.</a>] or [<a href="/savers/legname.html">Sponsor</a>] 
<br>
<font size=1>Savers &amp; Investors League, 1995<br></font>
</body>
</html>
